<HEADLINE> Duma Confirms Primakov as Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, on Friday endorsed Yevgeny Primakov's
nomination as prime minister by an overwhelmingly majority.
</P>
<P>
The Duma, voted 317-63 to confirm Primakov, in a major show of
support for the new government that ended a political standoff
between President Boris Yeltsin and the opposition-dominated Duma.
</P>
<P>
In a speech before the voting in the State Duma, Primakov said
that he would appoint communist Yury Maslyukov as first deputy
prime minister in his coming government.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to deputies to ratify the much-delayed START II
nuclear arms reduction treaty with the United States, saying he
would not back down on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he did not have an economic program because he
had only been nominated the day before, but economic reform would
continue.
</P>
<P>
"Reform are necessary. The present situation cannot be overcome
without reform," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for a strong state role in regulating the economy.
"The government should intervene into the economic affairs and
regulate them. This is not a return to the administrative and
command system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he wanted his cabinet members to put aside party
interests.
</P>
<P>
"Representatives of all parties should join the Cabinet as
professionals and work as members of a single team. And there
should be no orders from the organization they belong to," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign policy, Primakov said there would be no
confrontation with other countries. But it was vital to defend
Russia's national interests.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need confrontation, a return to the Cold War. And
that will not happen," he said. "But at the same time we will
strictly defend the interests of the state."
</P>
<P>
Saying that he was not yet well prepared for the job, Primakov
warned deputies against expecting quick results from his incoming
government as it strove to pull the country out of its acute
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He asked deputies to give his government up to a year before
deciding if it was succeeding or not.
</P>
<P>
"Without the decisive support of the Duma, and I want to
emphasize the word decisive, the government won't be able to
work," Primakov told the deputies.
</P>
<P>
"We need unity to come out of this very grave crisis," he
said. "Do not expect to continue political confrontation."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin nominated Primakov for premier on Thursday after the
Duma rejected Viktor Chernomyrdin twice for the prime minister's
post.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier on Friday that Russia is at a crucial moment
and that it is necessary to urgently lower prices, fill the shops
with goods again, restore the banking system, and guarantee the
safety of bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed those issues can be solved by the new
government under the leadership of Primakov with the support of
both the president and the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
