<HEADLINE> Nujoma to Visit Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma
will pay a state visit to Mozambique from September 15 to 17 at
the invitation of his Mozambican counterpart Joaquim Chissano,
the Mozambican ministry of foreign affairs said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, the ministry said Nujoma's
visit "is aimed at cementing the friendly and cooperative
relationship between the peoples and governments of the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
The two governments will also make an assessment of their
cooperation according to the agreement reached in 1990 by the two
BAP507PAB172I11TFQL00:1100:121664
nations, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
It added that the two presidents will exchange views on the
political, social and economic situations in their respective
countries as well as on the latest developments in the sub-region
and the continent.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano, as the vice chairman of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), insists that the military
conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo be resolved through
negotiations while Namibia nods at the military intervention of
Zimbabwe and Angola in a bid to help Congolese President Laurent
Kabila fight against the Tutsi-led rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
