<HEADLINE> Blair to Go Ahead with Clinton Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair will go ahead with his scheduled meeting with U.S. President
Bill Clinton during a visit to New York later this month,
according to Downing Street sources.
</P>
<P>
Blair, who is a close friend of Clinton, is now under
increasing domestic pressure to cancel his plans to meet Clinton
during a New York mini-summit about the "third way" on September
21 while the Clinton sex scandal is being blown out of
proportions.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman was quoted by Reuters as saying
early Friday Blair is still planning to stick to his original
plans of attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, what's going on in Washington right now is a matter
for the American people, and the American Congress. However, the
president (Clinton) has been a good friend and ally to this
country," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a close relationship with the United States and it's
important for this country to continue to have a close
relationship with the United States," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to Clinton's efforts in promoting the
Northern Ireland peace process, saying "The prime minister (Blair)
has said that no other American president has done as much for
peace in Northern Ireland as Bill Clinton." 
</P>
</TEXT>
