<HEADLINE> Italian Nun Still in Hands of Abductors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian nun Sister Marsa
is still in the hands of her abductors Friday as the
SOS-Mogadishu hospital remains closed for the second day.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the abductors, Sister Marsa is
in good health and fed well.
</P>
<P>
The nun who had been working in the main maternity and child
health care hospital of the capital was abducted Thursday morning
by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Sister Marsa is being kept by a third group of gunmen after
she was transferred twice. The abductors do not want to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed sources said the gunmen are demanding a ransom of
240,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, elders from the clan of those who kidnaped Sister
Marsa are trying their best to secure a safe release of the nun.
They hoped that she will be released very soon.
</P>
<P>
Sister Marsa is a well known nun especially in Mogadishu for
her long-term humanitarian activities in the SOS maternity
hospital during the years of the civil war.
M14-91NBB186i0911ql00:2800:280829
</P>
<P>
The abduction of Sister Marsa is believed to have been
prompted by the misunderstanding between the regional
headquarters of the SOS-International in Nairobi and the former
finance administrator of SOS in Mogadishu, Abdullahi Erro, who
was subsequently been replaced.
</P>
<P>
This misunderstanding has been further complicated by no
salary paid for the local staff of SOS in Mogadishu last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
