<HEADLINE> Taliban Claim New Gains in Central Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic
Taliban Friday claimed they had seized seven villages in the
central province of Bamyan following the defection of an
opposition commander and his troops, reports monitored here said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia advanced into villages in the districts of
Kohmard and Saighon as part of a fierce drive to take Bamyan,
stronghold of the anti-Taliban Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat, the reports
quoted the militia's mouthpiece Radio Kabul as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Haji Mohammed Moahqaq, a top leader of the
anti-Taliban northern alliance, denied that the Taliban had seized
the villages or his side's troops had joined the Taliban ranks.
</P>
<P>
The northern alliance, which groups forces loyal to
Uzbek-ethnic warlord Rashid Dostum, Afghanistan's former military
chief Ahmad Masood and the Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat, has suffered a
serious setback after the Taliban forces overran its headquarters
of Mazar-e-Sharif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
