<HEADLINE> Russian Sailor Threatens to Blow up Submarine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A sailor who killed seven
fellow servicemen on a submarine in Severomorsk, Murmansk region
in northern Russia early Friday, is now threatening to blow up
the submarine, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Kuzminykh refused to surrender despite words that his
parents were on their way to the site, Northern Fleet Prosecutor
Igor Yefremov said.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Zdanovich, spokesman for the Russian Federal Security
Service (FSB), said the submarine is not carrying nuclear
ammunition, adding that an FSB anti-terrorist unit is now at the
site of the incident and ready to deal with the actions of the
sailor inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
Force may have to be used, Interfax quoted Zdanovich as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kuzminykh is believed to be psychologically normal. He has
never sought psychiatric help.
</P>
<P>
He is now in the submarine's arms compartment, which contains
torpedoes and boxes with explosive substances, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday morning, Kuzminykh left the sub and went to the
mooring, where he seriously wounded a sentinel and seized his
automatic rifle.
</P>
<P>
He also wounded an officer who tried to stop him.
</P>
<P>
Kuzminykh then returned to the submarine and killed five
sleeping fellow sailors. He took two other sailors hostage and
killed them later.
</P>
<P>
The submarine, one of the Northern Fleet's eight "Akula" type
vessels, joined the fleet in 1984.
</P>
<P>
A source in the fleet's headquarters earlier told Interfax that
these submarines are fitted with one nuclear plant and may also be
equipped with Shkval missiles or torpedoes with nuclear warheads.
</P>
</TEXT>
