<HEADLINE> China's Envoy on Question of Taiwan's UN Reentry (2) BAP527IAE028S11PEQL00:3900:391736 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan has been an
inalienable part of China since ancient times, China stressed here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the General Committee of the 53rd Session of the
General Assembly, Qin Huasen, Chinese Permanent Representative to
the United Nations, said both the 1943 Cairo Declaration and the
1945 Potsdam Proclamation reaffirmed China's sovereignty over
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin said to date, 162 countries have diplomatic
relations with China and they all recognize that there is but one
China in the world, the Government of the People's republic of
China is the sole legal government representing China in its
entirety and that Taiwan is an inalienable part of the People's
republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Qin said over the period of nearly five decades since the
founding of the People's Republic of China, great changes have
taken place both in the world situation and in China which
includes Taiwan, in the social, economic, political and other
aspects.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that however, no such changes can alter the fact
that Taiwan is a province of China and that China exercises
sovereignty over Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
