<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Mauritius Sign Cultural Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting South
African President Nelson Mandela Friday signed two agreements
with Mauritian Prime Minister Nivinchandra Ramgoolam here after
close-door talks with him for half an hour in the morning.
</P>
<P>
These are a cultural accord for the period of 1998 to 2001 and
a bilateral pact on cooperation in sports and recreation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that these deals will enable the two nations to
promote and expand cooperation to the greatest possible extent
and to strengthen the friendly ties and mutual understanding
between the two peoples, said a statement issued by the Mauritian
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here Thursday afternoon for a two-day
state visit to the Indian Ocean island country, was also
conferred on Doctorate by the University of Mauritius during his
visit along with Ramgoolam, to the university late this morning.
</P>
<P>
At the conferment ceremony, Ramgoolam, who paid a state visit
to South Africa in February, referred Mandela to "a towering
personality of contemporary history, a leader of men, a
philosopher and a statesman," who has "ceaselessly throughout his
life championed the cause of justice, equality and freedom."
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Mandela is scheduled to address the National
Assembly of the Mauritian parliament in Port Louis, the capital.
</P>
<P>
After the visit, the 80-year-old South African president will
attend and chair the summit of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) in Grand Baie, north of Mauritius, scheduled for
September 13 and 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
