<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers Urged to Observe U.N. Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) have agreed to
tighten the control of airports and airspace in a bid to
implement the U.N. sanctions on Angola's opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement follows a recommendation from the ministers of
transport and communications who attended the two-day SADC
Council of Ministers meeting here in the north of Mauritius,
Alfred Nzo, South African Foreign Minister and chairman of the
Council said here Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Ministers will urge SADC heads of state and government who
will meet Sunday and Monday to endorse the decision and take
necessary measures to ensure compliance with the decisions
through SADC, the Organization of African Unity and the U. N. on
this matter, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation Security Council enforced its sanctions on
the opposition National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) earlier this year in the wake of the former rebel
movement's failure to comply fully with the Lusaka Protocol
signed in 1994 with the government.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Council meeting which will end Saturday also
decided to create a legal sector whose main objective would be to
provide guidance and coordination of policies, programs and
projects as well as advice Council on legal matters arising from
SADC activities, said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
The SADC cooperation with the United States and European Union
were also discussed by the ministers.
</P>
<P>
All 14 SADC members states were present at the Council meeting
Friday including the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and the
Seychelles, two new members which entered into the regional block
last year.
</P>
<P>
But Congo (K) was not represented by its senior ministers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende told the press
the Congolese Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo will head Congo's
ministerial delegation to attend the Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, Kongolo has not come due to security situation in his
country, said an official close to the Congolese delegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
