<HEADLINE> Tension Remains High in Lesotho: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tension rose to new
heights in Maseru, the capital of Lesotho, Friday when several
army officers in the Lesotho Defense Force were arrested in a
swoop, a report reaching here quoted informed sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The army officers were driven to the maximum security section
of the central prison in Maseru in army vehicles, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The number of officers arrested was not immediately known and
there has been no official comment on the surprise move.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of the officers followed weeks of speculation that
there were two opposing factions in the Lesotho army who took
different positions over the defiance by a large group of
protesters in the grounds of the Royal Palace in Maseru.
</P>
<P>
The political situation in the land-locked country has been
simmering because of alleged electoral fraud over the past six
weeks as the opposition supporters first squatted at the gates of
the Royal Palace and later moved inside the palace grounds.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that those arrested Friday were against
government orders to remove the protesters from the palace
grounds.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were a lot of troops movement in
Maseru Friday afternoon. South African Press Association quoted
South African High Commissioner to Lesotho Japhet Ndhlovu as
saying that he was unable to confirm reports of an attempted
coup.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know really what is happening. We can't tell what is
happening," Ndhlovu said.
</P>
<P>
Ndhlovu said he was trying to contact several Lesotho cabinet
ministers, but they were unavailable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
