<HEADLINE> Canada to Strengthen Agricultural Partnership with Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada is to strengthen
agricultural partnership with Mexico in order to ferment trade
with its southern neighbor within the framework of North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
A Canadian agriculture trade delegation to Latin America,
including Canada's Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Good, Lyle
Vlief, five provincial agriculture ministers and a group of
Canadian business leaders arrived here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A local paper quoted Vanclief as saying that the mutual trade
volume between Canada and Mexico already stands at over 800
million U.S. dollars and is steadily increasing.
</P>
<P>
Vanclief is to meet Mexico's Agriculture Secretary Romarico
Arroyo Marroquin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canada's agriculture and agri-food sector rakes in over 22
billion dollars annually, making up just under 9 percent of
Canada's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Canada companies are putting increasing emphasis on the
international partnership with other countries, said Vanclief.
</P>
<P>
"Canada understands the benefits of partnering -- greater export
sales, cost savings, control of quality and enhanced economic
benefits for both partners," the minister said. 
