<HEADLINE> Turkey Recalls Ambassador to Libya in Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has recalled its
ambassador to Libya to protest Tripoli's support for the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), the Anatolia News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Mufit Ozdes has been recalled for "consultations for
an indefinite period" to protest Libya's permission to a PKK group
to attend a parade on September 1, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Necati Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Libya has also withdrawn its ambassador to
Ankara, the semi-official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A number of PKK members in their national dress and carrying
PKK flags and pictures of PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan marched in a
ceremony marking the anniversary of the Revolution that brought
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi to power.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will not tolerate Libya's public support for its
outlawed guerrilla group, Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish
state in the southeast of Turkey. More than 35,000 people have
been killed in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Libya, among other countries, of supporting
the PKK. Reports said that some 400 PKK members are believed based
in the North African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
