<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Says to Have Done Well in Reviving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi said Friday his government has made significant progress in
efforts to revive the battled economy but still needs urgent and
sustained action to fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
"We have made considerable progress on many of the issues"
troubling the Kenyan economy since this year, Moi said at the
one-day second Economic Consultative Meeting attended mainly by
cabinet ministers and other senior Kenyan officials. The first
was held in May.
</P>
<P>
Budget deficit, domestic debt and interest rates went down as
revenue collection rose, privatization moved forward and the
rehabilitation of infrastructure extensively damaged by the El
Nino rains is being undertaken, said Moi.
</P>
<P>
The May meeting resolved that the key means to revamp economy
are to cut public expenditure and re-build roads and other
collapsing infrastructure, partly in a bid to save tourism,
Kenya's No. 1 foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
Moi said the budget deficit for the financial year 1997/98
(July/June) reduced marginally to 2.4 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) from 2.5 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Revenue collection increased to over 168 billion Shillings (60
Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar). The stock of domestic debt
has also been reduced to 145.5 billion Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates in the eastern African country declined to 22.9
percent earlier this month from 27 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has also concluded credit agreements
with the World Bank and the African Development Bank for the
rehabilitation of infrastructure and has approved the setting-up
of the Kenya National Roads Board.
</P>
<P>
The country has also made gains in the privatization of the
telecommunication, ports, railway and energy sectors, Moi
announced.
</P>
<P>
"Privatization process for Kenya Ports Authority and Kenya
Railways has been approved by my government," said Moi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan parliament has also passed a bill to split the
Kenya Posts and Telecommunications Corporation into three
sr organizations.
</P>
<P>
Power purchase agreements have been concluded by the
government with a number of independent power producers.
</P>
<P>
"Civil service reforms, recruitment in the civil and teaching
services has been deferred and a freeze on increases of salaries
and allowances has been effected," Moi said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he expressed deep concern about rampant corruption
which has hurting Kenya's economy for years.
</P>
<P>
"One area in which corruption is most rampant as well as
destructive to the economy is in revenue collection," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moi said the government now is taking further measures to
fight against the evasion of duty and the dumping of cheap
imports, especially on sugar importing, into the country.
</P>
<P>
The final resolution of Friday's meeting is expected to come
out Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0028 </DOCNO>
