<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Amend Former Presidents Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Vice-President Christon Tembo
introduced to parliament Friday a bill on amendment of Zambia's
Benefits of Former Presidents Act aimed at streamlining the
provisions relating to former presidents when they retire.
</P>
<P>
Once passed, the bill will enable former presidents when they
retire to live in houses and places of their choice not more than
two years after retirement.
</P>
<P>
The existing act will in particular be amended by the
insertion in the appropriate place of the definition of "active
politics" as:
</P>
<P>
"The doing of any act indicating a person's intention to hold
elective or appointive office; or the holding of elective office
or appointive office in a political party or in an organization
whose main aim is the furtherance of political objectives."
</P>
<P>
In the principle act which was read together with the bill,
Zambia's former presidents are deemed not to have retired if
still in active politics.
</P>
<P>
This bill came three months after Kenneth Kaunda, the land's
only former president and now leader of the country's largest
opposition party, the United National Independence Party (UNIP),
declared last June after his release from five-month detention
that he would retire from "active party politics".
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was detained last December allegedly in connection with
the foiled military coup on October 28, 1997. He was charged with
misprisionment of treason which was denied by the former
president.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, the state withdrew the charges against Kaunda and
he was released. Local reports said his release was part of a
political deal brokered by South African President Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government, under the deal, agreed to withdraw all
the charges on condition that Kaunda, who was defeated by
President Frederick Chiluba in the 1991 multi-party elections
after 27 years' rule, retired from active party politics.
</P>
<P>
State House spokesman Richard Cakala said two weeks ago that
the government had offered Kaunda a house as part of his
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, Kaunda has been living in a house rented by
the Zambian government but the rentals amounting to about two
billion Kwacha or one million U.S. Dollars have never been paid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Envoy on Question of Taiwan's UN Reentry (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) --In its resolution 2758
(XXVI) adopted in 1971 at its 26th session by an overwhelming
majority, the General assembly reaffirmed the "one China "
principle in an exact and holistic matter, China said here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the General Committee of the 53rd Session of the
General Assembly, Qin Huasen, Chinese Permanent Representative to
the United Nations, said the General Assembly in the resolution
clearly and unequivocally recognized "that the representatives of
the Government of the People's Republic of China are the only
lawful representative of China to the United Nations and that the
People's Republic of China is one of the five permanent
representatives of the Security Council " and decided to restore
all rights of the People's Republic of China at the United Nations
and to expel immediately the representatives of Taiwan "from the
place which they unlawfully occupy at the United Nations and in
all the organizations related to it."
</P>
<P>
Qin said to restore the lawful seat of the People's Republic of
China at the United Nations and to expel the Taiwan authorities
from the United Nations are two indivisible aspects of one
question, and without expelling the Taiwan authorities from the
United Nations, it would have been impossible to resolve properly
China's representation at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin said only in this way could the resolution give,
as it did perfectly, concrete expression to the "one China"
principle and the Resolution 2758 (XXVI) has settled once and for
all and in a just and Comprehensive manner the question of China's
representation at the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Envoy on Question of "Taiwan's U.N. Reentry" (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- "The United Nations is
an intergovernmental organization composed of sovereign states,"
but "Taiwan, as a province of China, is in no position to join the
United Nations," a senior Chinese diplomat said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the statement at the General Assembly of the 53rd
Session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations is an intergovernmental organization
composed of sovereign states. Article 4 of the Charter of the
United Nations stipulates expressly that only sovereign states are
entitled to membership in the United Nations," Qin said. "Taiwan,
as a province of China, is in no position to join the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to principles of the international law,
the sovereignty of a State is indivisible, Qin said, "The
Government of the People's Republic of China naturally represents,
in the United Nations and its agencies, the Chinese people as a
whole, including the Taiwan compatriots."
</P>
<P>
"There dose not exist the so-called question of 'Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations'," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The question of Taiwan, by nature, bears no analogy to the
cases of Germany and Korea resulting from the international
agreements following the end of World War II," he said, adding
that "Therefore, the so-called principle of parallel
representation can not apply to Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
General Assembly resolution 2758 (XXVI) conforms to the Charter
of the United Nations and the principles of international law and
above all, reflects the actual situation in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In their attempt to challenge the resolution, the handful of
countries have naturally met with strong opposition from the vast
number of justice-upholding Member States of the United Nations,"
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-11 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Israeli Soldiers Clash After Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinians clashed Friday
with Israeli troops in protest against the killing of two Hamas
members by Israeli soldiers, leaving several Palestinians wounded,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Palestinians clashed with Israeli soldiers in the
West Bank town of Ramallah when they marched toward a nearby
Jewish settlement to protest the shooting of Imad Awadallah and
his brother who used to live near the city.
</P>
<P>
The protesters threw bottles and firebombs at the Israeli
troops guarding the settlement, who fired rubber bullets in
return, wounding a number of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians in other West Bank cities and Gaza also held
demonstrations after Israel sealed off the Palestinian self-rule
areas in the morning following the killing of the Awadallah
brothers, both Hamas members.
</P>
<P>
Awadallah and his brother were shot dead in an exchange of fire
with Israeli troops Thursday night in Hebron. Imad was suspected
of masterminding two suicide bombings in Jerusalem last year
killing dozens of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He escaped from a Palestinian jail in Hebron last month, where
he was imprisoned on charges of killing Hamas main bomb-maker Muhi
Sharif last March.
</P>
<P>
Hamas officials vowed Friday that they would take revenge on
the killing of the Awadallah brothers, saying Israel would pay
high price for the act, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
To ward off possible Hamas revenge, the Israeli army, on extra
high alert, announced late Thursday night that the West Bank and
Gaza would be sealed since early Friday, barring Palestinians from
entering Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel declared the closure at a time when the United States
Mideast envoy Dennis Ross is visiting Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas in a bid to bridge the gaps over the overdue
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met with Ross in the
afternoon. Details of the talks have yet to be disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
