<HEADLINE> Chinese Envoy on Question of "Taiwan's UN Reentry" (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- "The question of
Taiwan is purely an internal matter of China and a matter for the
Chinese people themselves that brooks no interference by any
country or individual in any way under whatever pretext," a senior
Chinese envoy said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the statement at the General Committee of the 53rd
Session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The settlement of the question of Taiwan and the reunification
of the motherland are the solemn and lofty missions of all the
Chinese people, including those on Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
As early as over a decade ago, on behalf of the Chinese
Government, Deng Xiaoping, the late Chinese leader, proposed the
fundamental policy of "peaceful reunification and one country, two
systems" for the settlement of the Taiwan question, he said.
</P>
<P>
On July 1 last year, the concept of "one country, two systems"
first materialized in Hong Kong and tremendous success has been
achieved ever since, he said, adding that on December 20, 1999,
China will resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The Taiwan question will be also resolved," he said, "it is
DPB288NBB200I11TSQL01:5501:565133
only a matter of when, and it will not drag on for too long."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, with the joint efforts of the people on both
sides of the Taiwan Strait, marked progress has been made in the
people-to-people exchanges between the two sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indirect trade has been growing rapidly every year and the
investment in the mainland by Taiwan business people has increased
steadily, he said, adding that the exchange of personnel visits
between the two sides has surpassed 12 million persons/times in
total.
</P>
<P>
The contacts and exchanges in the cultural, academic, sports,
VHK226NBB200I11TSQL01:5501:565138
scientific and technological, and journalistic fields have been
expanding vigorously, he said, adding that progress has also been
made in the postal and transport services between people on the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
The economic, trade and cultural exchanges between people on
the two sides of the Strait are closer than ever, which have
greatly deepened their mutual understanding and fraternal feeling,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Raising the question of the so-called "Taiwan's membership at
the United Nations" under such circumstances, the handful of
countries are only moving to severely sabotage the process of the
peaceful reunification of China, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
