<HEADLINE> Rebels Ready for Long-Term Guerilla War Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Rebels in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) is ready to wage long-term guerilla war
against President Laurent Kabila, a senior rebel leader said.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview by the Maputo-based Metical
newspaper, Wamba dia Wamba, leader of the rebel Congolese
Democratic Coalition, said in Goma in eastern Congo (k) that they
are ready to fight a long-term war against Kabila as what the
Angolan and Mozambican peoples did during their struggle against
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
Wambo said that any attempt for an end of conflict in DRC
without the involvement of his Movement would mean to delay the
solution of the crisis, the Mozambican News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The question of Congo, Wambo said, should be solved by the
Congolese people themselves.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is unrealistic to reach a real cease-fire
agreement at the Addis Ababa defence ministers meeting without
the involvement of the major players, adding that the major
players are the Congolese Democratic coalition, Zimbabwe, Angola
and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
He did not list Kabila as a major player, "as he does not have
his own army."
</P>
<P>
The Congolese Democratic Coalition was kept outside the
seven-nation peace summit held in Victoria Falls in Zimbabwe, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Victoria Falls peace summit, Wambo said that they were
invited to the meeting, but it turned out that they were treated
like prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his wish that the summit could have accepted
them. " Whatever the situation, leaders at the summit have to
accepted the existence of rebels," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are not interested in power, we only hope to clear our
country of the obstacles in building a democratic government," he
said, "We do not wish to have disaster, corruption and racial
genocide."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said that his movement has not any direct
contact with Mozambican President oaquim Chissano, but he said
they would like to contact him.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that President Chissano could use his influence to
let his colleagues know that to support Kabila means to support
the continuation of genocide, and the destabilization in southern
Africa," Wamba said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano, the Vice-Chairman of Southern African Development
Community (SADC), advocates to solve the DRC crisis through
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
