<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani Friday
vowed that Iran will take revenge on the Afghan Taliban militia
for its killing of nine Iranian diplomats in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani promised to families and relatives of the victims
that Iran will surely do so at the Friday prayers here.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban confirmed Thursday that the nine Iranian nationals
missing last month have been killed by "renegade forces" and
pledged to punish those responsible. (BC-Iran-Taliban-Rafsanjani)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Mohsen Aminzadeh said
on Friday that two of the 11 Iranian diplomats succeeded in
escaping the massacres of the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh told the official news agency IRNA that the two
diplomats found a chance to flee the Taliban's killing after the
group captured Mazari Sherif in the north of Afghanistan last
month.
</P>
<P>
He said that one of them was wounded but able to leave the city
with the help of a friend. (BC-Iran-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel has clamped a closure on the West Bank and
Gaza Strip beginning Friday morning and declared a nationwide
security alert following the killing of two Palestinian militants
Thursday night by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army announced the decision Thursday night after
the two armed Palestinians were shot dead in an exchange of fire
with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
After the seal-off went into effect at 4:00 a.m., all
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza were not allowed to enter
Israel. Meanwhile, Israeli army said its forces were put on extra
high alert, roadblocks were beefed up and reinforcements have been
dispatched. (BC-Israel-Palestine-Closure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- As U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross'
mission continues, his shuttles between Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators indicate that security issues take the center stage in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Since his return to the region Wednesday, Ross has held two
rounds of talks with the Palestinians - one with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat in Ramallah Wednesday, another with
Palestinian negotiators Abu Ala, Abu Mazen and Saeb Erekat here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ross also met with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and President Ezer Weizman here Thursday, and held another meeting
with Netanyahu, together with his four inner cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Those discussions showed that both the Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators focused their attention on the the U.S. proposal as a
package, looking at the specifics of such key issues as security
cooperation, along with Israel's troop redeployment in the West
Bank. (BC-Israel-Ross)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinians clashed Friday with Israeli troops in
protest against the killing of two Hamas members by Israeli
soldiers, leaving several Palestinians wounded, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Palestinians clashed with Israeli soldiers in the
West Bank town of Ramallah when they marched toward a nearby
Jewish settlement to protest the shooting of Imad Awadallah and
his brother who used to live near the city.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians in other West Bank cities and Gaza also held
demonstrations after Israel sealed off the Palestinian self-rule
areas in the morning following the killing of the Awadallah
brothers, both Hamas members. (BC-Israel-Palestinians-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has recalled its ambassador to Libya to
protest Tripoli's support for the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK), the Anatolia News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Mufit Ozdes has been recalled for "consultations for
an indefinite period" to protest Libya's permission to a PKK group
to attend a parade on September 1, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Necati Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Libya has also withdrawn its ambassador to
Ankara, the semi-official news agency said. (BC-Turkey-Libya)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus Friday welcomed statements made by the United
States President Bill Clinton that his administration is working
to help establish a bizonal and bicommunal federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the credentials of Cyprus' new ambassador to the
U.S. on Thursday, Clinton said that any solution to the Cyprus
issue should be "based on a bizonal, bicommunal federal framework
under U.N. auspices."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks came a few days after Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash proposed the establishment of a confederation of
"two equal and sovereign states" on the eastern Mediterranean
island. The Cypriot government has rejected the proposal.
(BC-Cyprus-US-Clinton Statements) 
