<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Backs China on Taiwan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Argentina
diplomat on Friday called on the General Committee of the 53rd
Session of the General Assembly to exclude the so-called
question of "Taiwan's Representation at the United Nations" from
the agenda of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Petrella, Argentina's permanent representative to the
United Nations, said that the representatives of the Government of
the People's Republic of China are "the only lawful"
representatives of the China at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine envoy described Taiwan as "an inalienable part" of
the People's Republic of China while upholding the principle of
the General Assembly resolution 2758 (XXVI).
</P>
<P>
In 1971, the General Assembly at its 26th session adopted by an
overwhelming majority such a historically significant resolution
which clearly and unequivocally recognized "that the
representatives of the Government of the People's Republic of
China are the only lawful representatives of China to the United
Nations and that the People's Republic of China is one of the
five permanent representatives of the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"Argentina is not in favor of including a new item regarding
the so-called 'Taiwan's representation at the United Nations'
since the issue has been resolved, and what Argentina is in favor,
however, is to see the matter resolved quickly within a highly
possible time framework which will be beneficial to the Chinese
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee of the 53rd Session of the General
Assembly met on Friday morning to adopt the agenda and
allocation of items for the current session.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Kazakhstann, Sri Lankan, Iraq, Kuwait,
Georgia and Mexico also took the floor to support Beijing on
Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee has, for five years in a roll since
1993, refused to put the question of so-called "Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations" in the agenda of the
General Assembly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0046 </DOCNO>
