<HEADLINE> Truce in DRC May Become Reality: Namibian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma said Friday that a cease-fire may soon become a reality
in the war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), South African
national television, the SABC, reported.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma was speaking in a special address to the Namibian nation on
the situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"This (The cease-fire) is the scenario which we all agreed to. The
rebels indicated that they would accept the cease-fire once it is in
place," Nujoma said.
</P>
<P>
He said details for implementing a cease-fire was being thrashed
out by defense ministers and senior military personnel in the
headquarters of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He said the democratization process will be carried out by the DRC
government and its people with the assistance of the OAU, the United
Nations and invited parties.
</P>
<P>
"Once the cease-fire arrangements are finalized, the parties
concerned will be convenient at a mutually agreed venue to sign the
agreement, thus setting the transition process in motion," said
Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the military intervention by his own country along
with Angola and Zimbabwe was made on behalf of the Southern African
Development Community to protect the DRC foreign invasion by Uganda
and Rwanda. 
</P>
