<HEADLINE> Iraq, Kuwait Back Beijing on Taiwan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Kuwait Friday
asked the General Committee of the 53rd Session of the General
Assembly not to put the so-called question of "Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations" in the agenda of the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Both Mideast countries recognized that the government of the
People's Republic of China is the sole legitimate government
representing the Chinese people as a whole and that the Taiwan
issue is an internal affair of China.
</P>
<P>
"It simply wastes time" for Taiwan to seek reentry into the
United Nations, a senior diplomat from the Iraqi U.N. Mission
said.
</P>
<P>
The question of the so-called "Taiwan's representation at the
United Nations" has long been "a settled matter" and there is no
need for further discussion.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, the General Assembly at its 26th session adopted by an
overwhelming majority the historically significant resolution 2758
(XXVI). In this resolution, the General Assembly clearly and
unequivocally recognized "that the representatives of the
government of the People's Republic of China are the only lawful
representatives of China to the United Nations and that the
People's Republic of China is one of the five permanent members of
the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Together with Iraq and Kuwait, representatives of Argentina,
Kazakhstan, Sri Lanka, Georgia, Mexico and Saint Lucia all took
the floor to support Beijing on the Taiwan issue, and spoke
against the interference in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee Friday met to adopt the agenda and
allocate items for the current session. The committee resumed its
meeting Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee has, for five years in a roll since 1993,
refused to put the so-called question of "Taiwan's representation
at the United Nations" in the agenda of the General Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
