<HEADLINE> Former Mayor of Rwanda Transferred to UN Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 11 (Xinhua)-- A former mayor of
Mukingo Province in Rwanda, Juvenal Kajelijeli, was transferred
Friday to the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR)
detention facility in Arusha, north Tanzania, from Benin, where
he was held in connection with the 1994 Rwanda genocide.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the United Nations
information center here Friday, Kajelijeli was arrested and
detained in Benin on June 5 in response to a request by the
tribunal's prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of Kajelijeli brings the number of people
presently detained in Arusha to 31 in connection with the
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR was created by the UN Security Council in November of
1994 after one of the intense periods of mass exterminations in
human history. At least 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
massacred in Rwanda by Hutu extremists in just three months in
the middle of that year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said that the tribunal's trial
chamber one will hold the pre-sentencing hearing of the Akayesu
case on September 28.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu, the former mayor of Taba, was found guilty of nine
counts of genocide and crimes against humanity on September 2. It
is expected that he will be sentenced soon after the
pre-sentencing hearing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
