<HEADLINE> World Bank to Cut Aid to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will reduce
its support to Kenya unless the country makes sustained political
commitment to reforms, Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Due to low absorptive capacity, the World Bank intends to
reduce its commitments to Kenya from the current 200-250 million
Dollars to 75-150 million Dollars per annum," he said at the
one-day second governmental economic consultative meeting here.
</P>
<P>
It was said that only three percent of dozens of World Bank's
economic development projects in Kenya has been successfully
implemented.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will only withdraw the decision "until there is
successful implementation of the medium-term expenditure
framework and sustained political commitment to reforms," Nyachae
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he announced that the government would soon resume
talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for resumption
of the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF), suspended
in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Government expected an IMF team in the
country late next week to undertake a preliminary survey and that
he is optimistic IMF would resume the suspended
multi-million-Dollar aid package as the government has been
committed to economic recovery..
</P>
<P>
Officials from the World Bank, IMF, European Union attended
the meeting presided by President Daniel arap Moi and attended by
almost all cabinet ministers and other senior Kenyan officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
