<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Report Released, Clinton Rebuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Friday approved to release a prosecutor's report
that accuses President Bill Clinton of perjury and obstruction of
justice in the Monica Lewinsky affair, but the White House
immediately rebutted it and denied almost all alleged grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The House voted 363-63 to release the 445-page report via the
Internet in the same day despite the objections of some Democrats
who argued it was unfair that Clinton didn't get a chance to see
it first.
</P>
<P>
Starr's report accused Clinton of repeatedly lying under oath,
witness tampering, obstructing justice and abusing his
presidential power in a damning report on his affair with Monica
Lewinsky made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, following
his eight-month investigation into Clinton's relationship with
Lewinsky and whether he tried to cover it up, contained
allegations of 11 potentially impeachable offenses and graphic
descriptions of their sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
The report alleged five counts of lying under oath, four counts
of obstructing justice, one count of tampering with a witness and
one count of abusing his constitutional authority by "lying to the
public and the Congress in January 1998 about his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky."
</P>
<P>
Starr's report specified sexual acts between Clinton and
Lewinsky that the prosecutor said were included under the legal
definition of sexual relations and that meant Clinton lied about
it.
</P>
<P>
Starr's investigation and release of his report has thrown
Clinton's presidency into crisis and threatened to lead to the
first impeachment proceedings against a president since Richard
Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Within an hour after the House approval, Clinton's lawyers sent
Congress a rebuttal saying the president had done nothing that
warranted impeachment.
</P>
<P>
"The president has acknowledged a serious mistake -- an
inappropriate relationship with Monica Lewinsky.... This private
mistake does not amount to an impeachable action," Clinton's
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton denied for seven months that he had a sexual affair
with Lewinsky but after testifying under oath to Starr's grand
jury in August he admitted having an "improper relationship" with
her.
</P>
<P>
The House action came hours after Clinton told religious
leaders at a White House prayer breakfast that he had sinned, and
asked the nation, his family and Lewinsky for forgiveness. It was
the first time Clinton asked for forgiveness from Lewinsky,
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said that he would defend against any impeachment
efforts and would remain on the job and said he had instructed his
lawyers "to mount a vigorous defense using all available,
appropriate arguments."
</P>
<P>
Most opinion polls indicated the American people did not want
the country put through presidential impeachment or resignation. A
new CBS poll conducted over the past three days showed 58 percent
of the 1,132 polled wanted the whole matter dropped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
