<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Power Plant Begins Operation in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The first private power plant
in Bangladesh, the 110-megawatt Khulna Barge-Mounted Power Plant,
started operation in the southwestern part of the country
Saturday, thus putting an end to state monopoly on power
generation.
</P>
<P>
"With this power plant, a new dimension has been added to
private-sector investment in the era of free market economy,"
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said while inaugurating the plant,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
All power-sector operations, including billing and
distribution, would be gradually privatized, she said.
</P>
<P>
Work has begun for separating production, transmission and
distribution to improve power management in the country, with the
formation of the Power Grid Company of Bangladesh for this
purpose, Hasina was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 103 million-U.S. dollar power plant, owned by the Khulna
Power Company, would provide relief to the power crisis-ridden
Khulna zone, and the company would sell electricity to the
National Power Development Board under a 15-year term, according
to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The country's average daily electricity demand is 2,300 mw
against an output of about 2,000 mw. As a result, loadshedding is
very common across the country, particularly during the summer
season from March to June.
</P>
<P>
Hasina took over the Energy Ministry early this year after
dismissing Energy Minister Nooruddin Khan for failing to reduce
the frequency of loadshedding and improve the country's overall
power supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
