<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Breaks World Cup Athletics Record Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Marion Jones, the
United States sprint sensation, broke the women's 100-meter World
Cup record of 11.02 seconds on Saturday when she clocked 10.65
seconds at the Johannesburg Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Jones set a new World Cup record in the Women's 200m Friday
when she finished at 21.62 seconds.
</P>
<P>
This was also the second World Cup record set on the second
day of the 8th IAAF World Cup in Athletics, after Hungarian Tibor
Gecsek unleashed a 82.68m throw in the men's hammer earlier on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jones was followed by Chandra Sturrup from the Americas
contingent with 10.97, and Mary Onyali from Africa with 11.05.
</P>
<P>
In the men's triple jump, Charles Friedek created his seasonal
best with 17.42m and scored a gold for Germany. Denis Kapustin
from Russia won silver and contributed seven points to the
European men's team with 17.32m. Yoelbi Quesada from the Americas
team took the third with 17.25m.
</P>
<P>
Top athletes from around the globe braved the chilly weather
Saturday to compete for their continents at the quadrennial
showpiece in Johannesburg. The temperature stood at 12 degrees
Celsius and many athletes admitted they were affected by the cold
weather.
</P>
<P>
The African men's team, the reigning champion, topped the
standing list after 11 events were completed on Saturday. It won
66 points, followed by Americas and Europe, both with 57 points.
</P>
<P>
The women's teams from the United States and Russia took the
lead with 62 points each after 11 events were contested Saturday.
Europe got the third with 60 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
