<HEADLINE> Africa Grabs First Gold in 2nd Day of World Cup Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Africa snatched the
first gold medal in the second day of the World Cup Athletics
tournament on Saturday when Glory Alozie of Nigeria finished the
first in the women's 100-meter hurdles.
</P>
<P>
She ran 12.58 seconds, beating Angie Vaughn from the United
States with 12.67 seconds and Russian Irina Korotya with 12.77
seconds.
</P>
<P>
The European men's contingent also bagged a gold when Tibor
Gecsek from Hungary won the hammer throw event with 82.68m.
Gecsek broke the World Cup record of 82.12m in the event.
</P>
<P>
Heinz Weis from Germany unleashed a 80.13m throw and won the
second place, followed by Asian Andrew Abduvaliyev with 79.40m.
</P>
<P>
German Damian Kallabis got a surprise win in Men's 3000m
steeplechase when he beat hot favorite Kenyan Bernard Barmasai
and clocked 8:31.25 minutes. Bernard, the world record holder,
just ran second at 8:31.85. 
</P>
