<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Peace, Prerequisite for SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 12 (Xinhua) -- When leaders
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries
discuss ways to achieve economic integration here, they will have
to sort out the pressing peace crises in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ever since its founding in 1980, this regional organization
has been working hard toward coordinating and developing the
economy in the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
During its summit last year in Malawi, SADC leaders resolved
to achieve regional economic integration in the region by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, the armed revolt in Democratic Congo against Laurent
Kabila's 15-month old government, which has sucked in nearly half
of the 14 members of the regional grouping, and the crippli~?peace process in An
gola in the past year, has certainly become
two of the urgent issues for the heads of state and government
during their meeting here in Mauritius on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
The former Zaire is the largest country in central Africa,
with rich mineral resources coveted by many. Its entrance into
SADC, the most influential sub-regional organization, adds power
to the country's aim for high economic advancement.
</P>
<P>
But this move war"cut short when ethnic Tutsi rebels in Congo
(K) accused Kabila of corruption and nepotism for which they
started the armed revolt on August 2.
</P>
<P>
The rebellion, prompted by Kabila's order for the Rwandan
Troops which had helped him to assume power, to leave his country
on July 27, has soon spread from the east to the west of the
country. At one stage, the rebels even claimed to have
controlled one-third of Congo, Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
From the regional prospective, the Congo crisis has disturbed
the balance both inside the country and in the central and
southern African region.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the rebellion started in the east of Congo, Kabila
has accused Rwanda and Uganda, two former allies which assisted
him last year in ousting late dictator Mobuto Sese Seko, of
invading to back the Tutsi Banyamulenge rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Congo crisis has also divided the SADC members, with
countries led by South African President Nelson Mandela
advocating diplomatic settlement, whereas Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia have been favoring direct military intervention.
</P>
<P>
The latter have sent troops and weapons to the war-torn
country to prop up Kabila's government and turned the tide in
favor of Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Congo has now turned for the better, with the
government army and its allied troops routing the rebel soldiers
in the west of the country, forcing them to retreat to their
eastern strongholds.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here said Congo (K) will remain divided and
this poses threats to regional stability if the warring sides
cannot sit down for negotiations on a cease-fire, the withdrawal
of foreign troops and the possibility of transition to democracy
with a broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The SADC countries have been mediating the crisis in Congo
since the fighting broke out in early August, with many urgent
mini-summits called.
</P>
<P>
The peace summit at Victoria Falls in Zimbabwe ended without
an agreement on cease-fire, because President Kabila and his
backers did not recognize the rebel delegation and had
face-to-face talks with it.
</P>
<P>
Early this month another summit was called during the
Non-Aligned Movement summit in Durban, South Africa, with a
consensus reached on cease-fire and a peaceful settlement of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Again, a defense ministers meeting in Ethiopia this week
failed to achieve a breakthrough because Kabila and his allies
refused to deal directly with the rebels, and this caused Rwandan
and Ugandan delegates to walk out of the meeting hall.
</P>
<P>
Despite Mandela's public announcement of his understanding of
military intervention on the part of Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia, differences remain among SADC countries with regard to
approaches to the situation in Congo.
</P>
<P>
To eliminate these differences and restore peace is no doubt
the key and prerequisite for the region to concentrate its energy
back on economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Angola, a strife-torn country in the southern African
region, is another problem which has been calling for attention.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the country's independence from Portugal in 1975,
clashes between fighters of the People's Liberation Movement of
Angola (MPLA) and the National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) have been routine reports, until Lusaka Protocol
was signed in November, 1994 which initiated the protracted
Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
What's sad is that despite efforts made by the United Nations
and the SADC countries, the opposition UNITA has failed to comply
fully with the Protocol in terms of disarmament, handing over
strategic cities it occupied to the government and shifting its
headquarters to the capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The government hence suspended the function of UNITA members
in the national unity and reconciliation government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UNITA announced severance of its cooperation
with Russia, Portugal and the United States, the troika observer
missions on the Angolan peace process, and resumed fighting and
raids on government areas, and this has thrown the peace process
in the country into another crisis.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the continuing clashes in Congo (K) and
Angola will surely affect the overall economic development in the
region.
</P>
<P>
To restore peace in the two countries is therefore a matter of
urgency for the SADC before it can tackle with economic problems
important for achieving regional integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
