<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting on South Asian Gender Issues Ends in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting on gender
mainstreaming in the South Asian region ended here Saturday after
agreeing to strengthen what the countries have been doing and
share expertise.
</P>
<P>
Chandni Joshi, regional program advisor of the U.N. Development
Fund for Women (UNIFEM), described the meeting, the first of its
kind in the region, as very positive because there had been a very
sound work plan to be followed.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that every country felt that the exercises they
have done on gender mainstreaming especially at the planning level
need to be extended.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that there should be more sharing in
information and expertise in the region, she added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, organized jointly by the Nepali government and
UNIFEM, was building on the second South Asian regional meeting
held here on September 9 and 10 to commemorate the Fourth World
Conference on Women in Beijing in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed at the Beijing conference that gender
mainstreaming, which refers to a strategy for making gender
considerations an integral dimension in the design,
implementation, monitoring and evaluation of policies and programs
in political, economic and societal spheres, is one of the
fundamental strategies to achieve gender equality.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was represented by Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, all member countries of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
Joshi said there was a proposal that this kind of meeting be
held every two years to review what has been achieved in building
gender issues into development plans.
</P>
<P>
She said that as the participants were government officials and
representatives of very dedicated non-governmental organizations
from the SAARC countries, commitments made at the meeting can be
translated into practice.
</P>
<P>
She said budgetary constraint and gender sensitization at
different levels are among the major problems facing the SAARC
countries.
</P>
<P>
She noted that UNIFEM is working for political and economic
empowerment of women and eradication of gender-based violence in
the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Dominates Second Day of Pentathlon Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Hosts China began to show
their prowess on the second day of CISM 46th Military Pentathlon
World Championships, taking up top positions in both men and
women's events here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After a relatively indifferent shooting performances
yesterday, the Chinese turned themselves on in today's obstacles
running event, with three world record-smashing showings from
their women athletes.
</P>
<P>
Among them, Shen Liping became the new world record holder in
finishing the course with a time of two minutes 20.9 seconds,
bettering the old one set by Denmark's Heidi Olsen last year in
Sweden by 2.7 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The host women continued to sweep top four places in the
individual standings, with defending champion Wang Lianying leadin
g the table with 2,207.2 points.
</P>
<P>
The day ended with the Chinese women, who was fourth after
first day's shooting event, notching up top position followed by
Sweden on second and Denmark the third.
</P>
<P>
The things were all but the same in the men's events, with
China topping the table with 8,977.2 points, Brazil on second
with 8,840.7 and Sweden on third with 8,777.7.
</P>
<P>
Defending men's champion Carlos Silva of Brazil was the only
man on the day to break the Chinese domination, taking the
running course with a time of 2:13.8, beating China's Li Zhong
into third on 2:16.7.
</P>
<P>
"It's my best results in the competition," said the
33-year-old Silva, who participated for the second time in the
annual military sports meeting. "But I only concern about the
team's results."
</P>
<P>
But Li was still the overall leader with 2,282.1 points, his
teammate Zou Jun placed the second on 2,234.5. Silva was third on
2,232.4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
