<HEADLINE> Somalis Demonstrate for Release of Abducted Nun  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of women and
children demonstrated Saturday in front of the SOS Hospital in
by gunmen in the Somali capital Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They stressed their need for medical assistance as the
hospital had been closed since in protest, and blamed the
security guards of the hospital for allowing the gunmen to take
away the nun.
</P>
<P>
Efforts for the release of Sister Marsia have intensified
Saturday morning after the area, where the nun is being held, has
been sealed off to prevent the abductors from further
transferring her to other places as they have been doing since
the abduction.
</P>
<P>
The traditional elders of Eyr sub-clan led by Jama Botan and
Colonel John Dhorre have gone inside the building where Sister
Marsia is held in an effort to negotiate with the militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts are believed to have been behind the
surrendering of the nine militiamen, while the rest are expected
to give up later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The terms of the surrender is not known, however, a Toyota
Hilux pick-up escorted by an armed Nissan truck was made ready
for the surrendering militiamen giving up their evil activity of
hostage keeping.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed and Mogadishu's governor,
Hussein Ali Ahmed have both condemned the abduction of Sister
Marsia.
</P>
<P>
The local organization, Isma'il Jumale Human Rights Center,
has also strongly condemned the abduction of Sister Marsia.
</P>
<P>
The human rights center said in a statement issued today that
they are registering all evil activities and their perpetrators
for a possible tribunal in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
