<HEADLINE> Tension Mounts in West Bank After Killing of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 13 Palestinians
were injured in clashes with Israeli soldiers on Saturday as
tension has mounted in the West Bank following the killing of two
Palestinians on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said 10 Palestinians injured in Ramallah
and three in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio reported that an explosive device went
off near an army vehicle Friday night, but it did not give further
details.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers shot dead Imad Awadallah and his brother in
Hebron. Israeli Defense Ministry said the two were on their way to
a major attack against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said Awadallah brothers were leaders of a
military wing of Hamas, or the Islamic Resistance Movement, and
were behind two deadly suicide bombings in west Jerusalem last
year which killed dozens of Israelis and injured hundreds of
others.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza, Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin reportedly
convened a meeting of Hamas leaders Saturday. Yassin has vowed to
revenge for the shooting of Awadallah brothers, saying Israel
would pay high for the act.
</P>
<P>
Put on high alert, Israeli army declared a closure of the areas
and Gaza beginning early Friday morning, barring all Palestinians
from entering Israel.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, about 2,000 Palestinian students demonstrated in
the Palestinian-ruled West Bank city of Nablus, calling for a
revenge for the killing of Awadallah brothers and a halt to the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has denounced the killing
of two Palestinians, saying there is no hope for progress in the
peace process if Israel continues with such policies.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross is in Nablus Saturday
for the second meeting with PNA President Yasser Arafat. The two
met for the first time Wednesday night, several hours after Ross
arrived in the region on a mission to narrow the gaps between
Israel and the Palestinians over the overdue Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross is expected to report to Arafat about his two rounds
of talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu held on
Thursday and Friday, during which no progress has been reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
