<HEADLINE> No Progress Reported After Ross' Two Rounds of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- There has been no progress
reported in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process after
U.S. Middle East Peace Envoy Dennis Ross concluded on Saturday
his second rounds of mediation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Ross met again with Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat in the West Bank
city of Nablus on Saturday. But they did not speak to reporters
about their discussions.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Ross will continue to make efforts to
narrow gaps between Israel and the Palestinians over the Israeli
troops' second redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for the third time on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report of local daily Haaretz said that hammering
out a mutually acceptable security memorandum of understanding
between Israel and PNA has become central to the U.S. diplomat's
current mission to the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross will try to win Palestinian acceptance to modifications
to the draft that won the acceptance of security officials from
all sides last December. Netanyahu scuttled the draft, objecting
to reference that required equal enforcement against extremism on
both Israeli and Palestinian sides.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to achieve this goal, Ross also met with Israeli
security cabinet members during the second round talks with
Netanyahu on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian peace process has been stalled for
months over the scope of next Israeli pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. plan reportedly called on Israel to hand over 13
percent of the West Bank in the next withdrawal in return for the
fulfillment of the Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
PNA has formally accepted the plan, while Israel insists that
it would consider the plan only after the PNA ensured the security
of the Jewish country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
