<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Urges Halt to Rampant Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The State Forestry
Administration has urged that rampant logging be strictly banned
to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
Li Changjian, deputy director of the administration, told a
national conference on protecting forests here today that the work
is arduous and the situation is severe.
</P>
<P>
Every year, some 6.6 million mu (440,000 hectares) of forests
are cut down. Last year, 600,000 cases relating to illegal logging
were reported, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official announced that the administration will launch a
crackdown on illegal logging with police and law enforcement
officers from several central departments.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the farmland reclaimed since 1994, which was
previously woodland, must be used for re-planting trees before
2000.
</P>
<P>
Rampant logging has caused massive soil erosion along the
Yangtze River and other major rivers, which was a key factor that
triggered the deluge this summer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
