<HEADLINE> Legislature Concludes Agricultural Inspection Tour in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, concluded a
10-day tour today in Southwest China's Yunnan Province to inspect
the enforcement of agricultural law.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the law-making body, joined the tour.
</P>
<P>
According to the inspection team, local governments and farmers
have benefited a great deal from enacting the Agriculture Law and
the Law on Spreading Agricultural Technologies.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels have abolished 1,500 illegal projects
that over-burdened farmers economically in accordance with the
law, the team said.
</P>
<P>
The inspection team also noted that, by ensuring investments
provided for by the law, the province has improved its
agricultural infrastructure, benefited from good harvests for 10
consecutive years, and increased farmers' income accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province's grain output exceeded 12
million tons in 1997, 18.9 percent more than five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, the team told the provincial government that more
efforts are needed to modernize and industrialize its farming
business to bring prosperity to underdeveloped areas in the
province, while close attention should be paid to the environment
and ecological preservation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
