<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Leprosy Congress Closes in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the 15th
International Leprosy Congress in Beijing were urged today to work
together to eliminate leprosy in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The goal of creating a world without leprosy is unlikely in the
foreseeable future, but experts and social workers all over the
world should plan realistic actions which could solve problems
related to leprosy, both medical and social, said Yo Yuasa,
president of the International Leprosy Association at today's
closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"With the first congress in Berlin in 1897, the modern fight
against leprosy had started and made noteworthy progress, bringing
us to where we stand now," Yuasa said. "With this 15th congress in
Beijing we are starting the second century of our fight which
should hopefully take us to our stated goal."
</P>
<P>
He said this congress is "forward-looking" and
"action-oriented." In addition to academic exchanges on the
control and treatment of leprosy, the congress highlighted social
aspects of the disease, aiming to eliminate discrimination against
people affected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
More than 730 foreign and nearly 400 Chinese delegates,
including more than 100 victims of leprosy who have recovered,
attended the six-day congress. The next congress will be held in
Brazil in 2003.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the closing ceremony 124 institutions, hospitals and
clinics and more than 200 individuals specializing in leprosy
control were honored by the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, about 85 percent of Chinese counties and
cities have lowered the prevalent rate of leprosy below 0.1 per
10,000, and 13 percent of counties and cities were near the
standard, said Cao Ronggui, vice minister of health.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, about 2,000 new leprosy patients were detected
in China per year, and about 200,000 who recovered from the
disease are living in China at present, according to Cao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
