<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM Dismisses Coup Reports in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo Saturday dismissed reports of an attempted
coup in Lesotho as unfounded, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
"It was just some problems in the army itself, it's not a coup
as such. We think the situation is not as bad as earlier
reported," said Nzo, who has been in Mauritius attending a
two-day meeting of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC)'s council of ministers.
</P>
<P>
The commander of the Lesotho Defense Force, Makhula Mosakheng,
resigned on Friday night and brigadier-commander Thibeli had
taken over the running of the army.
</P>
<P>
He also announced on Radio Lesotho the dismissal of 26 senior
officers citing the reason of "the public interest".
</P>
<P>
The sudden resignation followed a day of dramatic events
during which junior officers arrested some senior officers of the
defense force.
</P>
<P>
Nzo said a report into alleged electoral fraud in Lesotho
would be discussed at the SADC annual summit which gets underway
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the report, which was compiled by a three-nation
commission led by South Africa, had not yet been handed to South
African President Nelson Mandela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
