<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS: Updated with casualties hke --Three Wounded by Gunfire in Cambodia Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 12 (Xinhua) -- At least three people were
wounded by gunfire as Cambodian government supporters and
opposition protesters clashed Saturday just off Phnom Penh's main
business street, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
A boy and a man in his twenties were wounded in their legs by
gun shots, while another man was bleeding from a chest wound,
after a volley of shots fired by the pro-government demonstrators
near the city's Monivong Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian opposition parties had earlier called off a planned
Sunday protest rally after 5,000 supporters of the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) demonstrated on Saturday, bringing the
worsened tension between the government and opposition into the
sixth day.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen's supporters marched through streets in Phnom Penh by
dozens of trucks and held rally in front of the Royal Palace.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, who carried sticks and stones and waved
placards supporting the results of the July 26 elections, demanded
the arrest of the two opposition political leaders of Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy, who complained about election
fraud.
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh called the demonstration a habitual practice
of Hun Sen's men.
</P>
<P>
"If the government dares arrest me, the bloodshed will continue
and it will be impossible to form a new Assembly and government,"
the prince warned.
</P>
<P>
The prince also said that the opposition has agreed to cancel
its planned mass rally of 20,000 supporters on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"In order to ease the tension of bloodshed in the capital, we
have decided to postpone our mass demonstration tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won 64 of the 122 National Assembly seats in the
Election, short of the two-thirds required to form a government
alone.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen offered to form a coalition government with FUNCINPEC
and the Sam Rainsy Party, but the offer was turned down by the
opposition. The tension between the two camps badly worsened on
Monday, when riot police dispersed demonstrators by force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
