<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Extends Voter Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Electoral Commission
has declared that the voter registration period for the
forthcoming local government elections will be extended for
another week due to voter apathy throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with stake-holders in the electoral process in
Lusaka, commission chair-an Bobby Bwalya announced Friday that the
voter registration period which was supposed to end Sunday has
been extended to September 20, government-owned Times of Zambia
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The extension was necessary because of the poor turnout which
has seen only 59,000 people throughout Zambia compared to the
targeted 1.5 million eligible voters, according to Bwalya.
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that the commission was concerned with
the poor turnout of those registering and implored political
parties, non-governmental organizations and other pressure groups
to go flat out to educate the people on the importance of voting.
</P>
<P>
Bwalya said according to the 1996 register, the country had
2.2 million registered voters and that additional 1.5 million
voters are expected to be registered this year, bringing the
total to 3.7 million out of the country's 4.3 million eligible
voters.
</P>
<P>
Most of the opposition parties including the United National
Independence Party (UNIP) welcomed the extension of the voter
registration period and have pledged to step up civic campaigns
to educate members on the importance of registration.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambia Democratic Congress, one of the main
opposition parties, did not attend the meeting and said Friday
that it would not participate in any election organized by the
ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy govmrnment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
