<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Massing Troops to Bakassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has denied massing
troops to the disputed Bakassi Peninsula on its border with
Cameroun, media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters said in a statement in Lagos Friday
that reports to the effect was "misleading and untrue", adding
that Nigeria was still resolved to settle the dispute through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We hereby state categorically that Nigeria has not sent any
fresh troops to Bakassi of recent. We stand by our statement last
Tuesday that we will not do anything to escalate tension in
Bakassi, and will continue to seek peaceful means to resolve the
Bakassi issue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that "Nigeria will maintain this position because we
believe that with Cameroun's cooperation, the situation could be
settled peacefully."
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters in a statement Tuesday accused
Cameroun of producing tension in the disputed area by deploying
more troops last week.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun, however, has denied the accusation and affirmed its
commitment to peaceful co-existence with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have clashed for several times in the
last few years over the sovereignty of the oil-rich peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The dispute was filed to the International Court of Justice at
Hague by Cameroun in 1994, to the objection of Nigeria. The court
ruled in June 1998 that it has the jurisdiction over the case and
requested Nigeria to file its defense by March 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
