<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Cancels Rice Order From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has canceled an
order for 400,000 tons of rice from Thailand, citing high price as
the reason, a source at Thailand's Rice Exporters' Association
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will call a bid instead on Monday and Tuesday for
600,000 tons of rice from international sources.
</P>
<P>
Thailand might yet win the deal because supplies from other
countries are limited, said the source, who refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that up to 77 rice exporters from China,
Vietnam, India and Thailand were expected to enter the bid. About
10 Thai rice companies were expected to bid for the deal.
</P>
<P>
The source said he was confident that for such a large amount,
Thai exporters would have an edge over most potential sellers who
had limited supply. Vietnam last month announced controls on rice
exports.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Ministry of Food and Horticulture had signed a
memorandum of understanding last month to purchase a total of
500,000 tons of rice from Thailand. Of the total, 400,000 tons
worth more than 5 billion baht (125 million U.S. dollars) would be
paid for in cash. The remaining 100,000 tons would be paid for
over three years. However, a contract was signed later only for
the 100,000 ton portion of the order.
</P>
<P>
The source said he did not believe the price the Thai
government had quoted to Indonesia, about 280 dollars per ton, was
too high. He said Indonesia might seek credit terms.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that Indonesia might not get its rice any cheaper
next week, as the rice was trading at 285-287 dollars per ton.
</P>
</TEXT>
