<HEADLINE> Pak President Praises China's Religious Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Rafiq
Tarar on Saturday expressed his appreciation of China's religious
policy towards its 20 million Muslims.
</P>
<P>
He was talking to a five-member Chinese Muslim delegation
which called on him here Saturday afternoon. The delegation led by
Ma Xian, vice president of China Islamic Association, is visiting
Pakistan at the invitation of the Ministry of Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tarar said that he was glad to see that the Chinese Muslims
are leading a very happy life thanks to the government's religious
policy under which the Islamic culture and tradition are
well-maintained and protected.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese Muslims have done a great job in
promoting the Pak-China relations which are already very cordial.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to increase exchanges of delegations
between the two countries in order to further enhance their
time-tested friendship.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Raja Zafar-ul-Haq, minister for religious
affairs, also met with the Chinese delegation.
</P>
<P>
"There is tremendous goodwill and respect for China in
Pakistan and the Pak-China relationship is exemplary," Zafar said.
</P>
<P>
He also lauded China's foreign policy which is based on
principles of mutual co-existence and non-interference in the
internal affairs of sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed the confidence that the Pak-China
friendly relations will be further cemented in future and the two
countries would continue to enhance bilateral cooperation in
various fields. 
</P>
