<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Tide in Bay of Bengal Slows Recession of Waters: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- An unusually high tide in the
Bay of Bengal, whipped up by a low, has held back floods in
Bangladesh from receding, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The high tides have slowed recession of floods in the country
despite falling trend in some rivers contributing to the deluge,
the Daily Star Saturday quoted Sharif Rafiqul Islam, executive
engineer of the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Since the full moon occurred on September 5, the sea has been
experiencing an unusual surge which provided a sort of barrier to
the flood water rolling into the Bay," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the tide ebbs in two or three days after the full
noon, but "we are surprised at the exception," he said.
</P>
<P>
The tide height was measured at Changpur, where the Ganges and
the Brahmaputra (rivers) join the Meghna river before going down
to the Bay.
</P>
<P>
"On Thursday (September 10), the high tide was measured at a
record of 5.52 meters above the mean sea level and the low tide
was 4.72 meters, slightly less the highest ever recorded level of
4.86 meters during the 1998 floods," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What caused the sea to behave unusually still remained
unknown," he said. "This is under investigation...but we seem to
be nowhere near a conclusion."
</P>
<P>
The high tide could been triggered by the "low" which formed
over the Bay of Bengal on September 8, reactivating the monsoon
before moving towards the northwestern Indian state of Uttar
Pradesh, a senior meteorologist stated.
</P>
<P>
"It (the low) triggered heavy pressure on the tide level
inundating low areas on the coasts which were not flooded," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But this is not uncommon," he said, adding that the country
experienced a similar situation during the monsoon in 1995 when
heavy wind and high tide pushed surges further inland of Chandpur
for three days.
</P>
<P>
Barring heavy rainfall, the situation would improve gradually,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Normally it takes for usual monsoon floods up to 20 days to
recede, going down the Meghna estuary into the Bay," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Everything depends on the rains. If there is no further
rainfall in the upper catchment areas of the Ganges and the
Brahmaputra, both of which flow from India, the floods would start
receding from the next cycle of moon, some 20 days from now,"
another flood expert said.
</P>
<P>
The tide situation was also influenced by the rush of water
from the major rivers, keeping the water stagnant," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
