<HEADLINE> Malaysia, India Set Up Technical Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and India
formed a joint technical committee Saturday to identify and
implement science and technology projects that could benefit both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up immediately after the two countries
signed an agreement on cooperation in science and technology,
marking the first formal cooperation in the area.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here by Malaysian Science, Technology
and Environment Minister Law Hieng Ding and Indian Human Resource
Development and Science and Technology Minister Murali Manohar
Joshi.
</P>
<P>
Law said the committee comprising officials from both countries
would focus on cooperation in implementing projects related to
weather forecasting, space technology, medicinal plant and
traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
"India has very advanced technology in weather monitoring and
aerospace that we can learn from," he told reporters after the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said India is also keen to join Malaysia in developing the
information technology sector and participate in the Multimedia
Super Corridor.
</P>
<P>
Joshi said India would also cooperate with Malaysia in finding
the best ways to safeguard gene materials found in the diverse
animal and plant species in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue is very crucial because some of the valuable
plant and animal parts and extracts have been patented by
foreigners under their country's legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
