<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Growth Goes Down in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- After an increase of 5.4
percent from April to June, the first quarter of India's fiscal
year 1998-99, the country's industrial growth fell sharply in July
to 1.7 percent from 8.2 percent the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Data released Friday by the Central Statistical Organization
(CSO) showed that industrial growth in the first four months from
April to July of the current year has slipped to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector, which accounts for three-fourths of
the latest estimate of the Index of Industrial Production, grew by
3.7 percent during the April to July period as compared to a 5.6
percent growth achieved a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The sector only increased by 1.2 percent in July against 8.5
percent in the same month last year while it grew by 5.5 percent
in the first quarter of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
CSO said the slump in the manufacturing sector in July could be
attributed to the negative growth in consumer goods as well as the
lower rate of growth in basic and intermediate goods.
</P>
<P>
The growth of electricity, which had recorded a low 6.2 percent
cumulative growth a year ago, fell to 9.9 percent in the first
four months compared to 10.2 percent in the April-June period this
year.
</P>
<P>
The mining sector reversed the negative 0.3 percent growth in
the first quarter by posting a 2.9 percent growth in July, thereby
taking the cumulative growth in April-July to 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The all-important capital goods sector grew by 6.8 percent in
July to post a cumulative growth of 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Consumer goods recorded a negative growth of 0.5 percent in the
month due mainly to a 4.7 percent fall in consumer durables
segment, popularly known as the white goods sector.
</P>
<P>
Non-durable consumer goods grew by a marginal 0.7 percent
during the month, posting a cumulative growth of 2.5 percent in
April-July period against a negative 1.5 percent growth in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among industry groups, metal products and parts went up by 24.8
percent followed by paper and paper products with 14.2 percent.
The worst performer was cotton textiles with a negative growth
rate of 14.4 percent.

=09120901
NNNN
17:04 17:04 g # HAB
</P>
</TEXT>
