<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Prisoners Make Furniture, Crafts With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Inmates in a Ugandan prison
has made furniture, arts and crafts out of water hyacinth which
has been a big hazard to transportation, fishing activities and
power generation.
</P>
<P>
The 40,000-U.S.-Dollar water hyacinth utilization project,
which is located in Luzira Maximum Security Prison near Kampala,
was funded by the Global Environment Facility through the United
Nations Development Program, the Monitor daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners there reportedly scoop the weed from the lake,
slice it up and separate the stalk from the roots and leaves. The
stalk is sun dried and woven into beautiful chairs, stools, mats,
carpets, hand-bags and baskets for sale.
</P>
<P>
William Omaria, the state minister for internal affairs, was
quoted as saying he is satisfied with this project and calling on
the facilitators to extend the project to up-countryrs prisons such as
Jinja and Kigo where the weed is in abundance.
</P>
<P>
The prison also has a biogas production project, which
generates energy used in cooking at the prison. The gas is said
to have been produced from the leaves and roots of the water
hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of Uganda's shore of Lake Victoria is covered
with the weed. The country is now using mechanical means to
remove the weed from the lake surface which has been affecting
fish catch and transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya in Bid to Ease Interest Rate Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates in general
declined in the Kenyan money market in the past two months partly
due to governmental efforts, according to the September issue of
the Monthly Economic Review by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
Interest rate on the 91-days Treasury bill declined for the
fourth consecutive month to 23.7 percent in August from 24.7
percent in July, said the review available Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Inter-bank interest rate declined further to 17.3 percent in
July from 21.7 percent in June 1998 following a reduction in
government's borrowing requirement that allowed some liquidity to
be released from Treasury bills redemption.
</P>
<P>
7 Interest on three months of deposits with commercial banks
eased in line with the downward trend in the Treasury bill
interest rate to 19.9 percent in July from 21.2 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in the review that interest rates,
which are still high enough to discourage investment, are
expected to continue declining mainly on account of improved
government's fiscal positions.
</P>
<P>
The bank also announced that it is carrying out tough action
to ease the interest rate burden. The measures range from cutting
public spending and governmet domestic borrowing to improve
revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
As part of the efforts, the government is ready to hold talks
with the IMF team on the rsumption of IMF's aid loans later this
month.
</P>
<P>
More commercial courts have been established to speed up the
process of recovering banking institution's bad debts.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has lowered the cash ratio by two percentage
points to 13 percent since July 1998 to reduce the interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The CBK review blamed a series of factors for the current
relatively high level of real interest rates in the eastern
African country. They are:
</P>
<P>
-- Excessive demand for credit in the money market mainly
from domestic borrowing to finance the government deficit.
</P>
<P>
-- The past high interest rates associated with the massive
liquidity mop-up in 1994 following the financial infractions of
1992-93.
</P>
<P>
-- Large portfolio of non-performing loans that result from
imprudent lending practices and the fact that many Kenyans borrow
money but fail to service debt. The judicial system is also slow
in resolving commercial cases.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, non-performing loans now stand at around 20
percent of the total advances by the banks, leading the banks to
charge high interest rates even on new loans to cover for
possible defaulting on loan repayments.
</P>
<P>
-- Domination of loans market by a few institutions that
stifle competition. Out of the 55 commercial banks in Kenya, only
10 banks control more than 70 percent of total deposits and more
than 65 percent of the loans.
</P>
<P>
-- Low supply of loanable funds from the external sources is
mainly due to the ripple effects of the suspension of the
multi-million-Dollar aid loans by the International Monetary Fund
mid last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Expectation of higher than actual inflation in line with
the high inflation rates in the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Slows Down in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The increase in inflation
in Kenya over the past three months slowed down in August
following the sustained controled monetary expansion, stability
in the Shilling exchange rate and better supplies of basic foods.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is expected to continue declining in Kenya in the
coming months thanks to prudent monetary policies and improved
supply of basic goods, according to the September issue of the
Monthly Economic Review by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
7 The decline in the international prices of imports,
particularly oil, that has also contributed to slowdown in
inflation, said the review.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in inflation was seen in all kinds of food,
fuel and power, and miscellaneous goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Month-on-month inflation declined to 9.8 percent in August
from 11.4 percent in July, data from the CBK review indicate.
</P>
<P>
7 Average annual inflation declined to 8.4 percent from 8.6
percent over the last year.
</P>
<P>
The three-month overall annualized inflation fell to negative
13.6 percent in August from 10.4 percent in July. Three-month
annualized underlying inflation also remained low at 0.3 percent
in August.
</P>
<P>
The underlying average annual inflation however increased to
9.1 percent from 8.8 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
The down in the overall inflation over last month was more
pronounced in the goods and services purchased by the lower
rather than by the middle and upper income groups, said the CBK
review.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said it will make more efforts to reduce the
underlying month-on-month inflation to less than five percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the planned measures are to maintain annual expansion
in broad money supply in the year to June, 1999 at below 10
percent and to continue carrying out tight fiscal policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
