<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Divergent on E-commerce Definition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Experts who met in
Austin, Texas this week to discuss issues concerning e-commerce
could not reach consensus on the definition of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Paul Resnick, an associate professor at the University of
Michigan, said that e-commerce should be narrowly focused on
transactions over computer networks, reported Techweb Friday.
</P>
<P>
But James McAndrews, a researcher with the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York, said that e-commerce also includes credit card
transactions at local grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
"Electronic commerce is a larger category than just Web-based
commerce," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the customer goes into the store to purchase, he said,
the transaction is recorded electronically.
</P>
<P>
A software developer agreed with the wider scope of that
definition, saying, "It's everything binary. We are taking our
economy and digitizing it."
</P>
<P>
Kevin Koym, president of the software company Development
System Development, also supported the definition with wider
scope, saying e-commerce is not just the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it includes everything from learning about products
online and electronic transactions to online customer-service and
support, said Koym.
</P>
<P>
The National Science Foundation meeting, sponsored by the
Center for Research in Electronic Commerce at the University of
Texas, was aimed to develop a strategy for studying e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Forty people, including computer scientists, attorneys,
economists as well as government officials and industry
researchers, attended the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
