<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Sending Aircrafts to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday denied it
has dispatched military and civilian aircrafts to Bamyan, northern
Afghanistan, to help the Shiite Muslims who are fighting with the
Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Iran News quoted Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi as saying that the reports on the
landing of Iranian military and civilian planes at the Bamyan
airport "are false."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that considering the dire situation of innocent
men, women and children of Bamyan that is under the siege of the
Taliban forces, Iran would extend every possible humanitarian aid
to them.
</P>
<P>
The reports on Iran's dispatch of aircraft to Afghanistan came
after fierce fighting erupted in Bamyan between the Taliban and
its rival the Northern Alliance led by the ousted president
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been threatening to take revenge on the Taliban forces
for their killing of nine Iranian diplomats based in Mazari
Sharif, northern Afghanistan. The Taliban on August 8 took over
the city and occupied the Iranian consulate, where 11 Iranian
diplomats worked.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Iran's powerful State Expediency Council Hashemi
Rafsanjani, the former president, warned Friday that Iran would
carry out a well-designed revenge plan with "clear objectives" at
an appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here speculated it is a highly possible for Iran to
launch a military strike on the Taliban, as the country is
continuing its military buildup along the eastern border with
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps have deployed 70,000
troops in the northeastern border province of Khorasan since early
this month, while the Iranian army has massed forces along Iran's
border with Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
