<HEADLINE> Relief Assistance for Bangladesh Reaches 176 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The total commitment and
pledges made by 30 countries and a number of international
agencies has so far risen to 176 million U.S. dollars including
cash and kind and foodstuffs, The New Nation daily reported
Saturday quoting official sources.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi government has appealed to the international
community for 879 million dollars as relief assistance in cash and
kind for flood victims and rehabilitation work after recession of
the flood waters.
</P>
<P>
The countries which have responded to the appeal include
Australia, Belgium, Bhutan, Britain, Canada, China, Denmark,
Egypt, France, Germany, Iceland, India, Italy, Japan, Jordan,
South Korea, Kuwait, Luxembourg, the Maldives, the Netherlands,
New Zealand, Norway, Spain, Sri Lanka, Sweden, Switzerland,
Thailand, the United Arab Emirates and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a number of international agencies such as the United
Nations family, the International Federation of Red Cross and red
Crescent Societies have already pledged to assist the country to
conduct relief operation and post-flood rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi embassies in different parts of the world are
continuing their efforts to apprise host governments and
philanthropic organizations to respond to the appeal for
assistance, the official sources added.
</P>
<P>
The current over two-month-long deluge has already flooded
about two-thirds of the country's territory, affecting more than
30 million people in 47 of the country's 64 districts, with the
flood-related death toll reaching 843 so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
