<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Refusal to Taiwan Move at UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today that any act that
contradicts the purpose and principles of the U.N. Charter and
relevant resolutions of the U.N. General Assembly and that
interferes in the internal affairs of other countries is bound to
meet opposition from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark after the General Committee of the on-going
U.N. General Assembly refused again on September 11 the proposal
by a small group of countries asking for listing so-called
Taiwan's representation to the U.N. on the agenda of the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
This has fully demonstrated the firm will of the vast majority
of the U.N. member states to safeguard the U.N. Charter, the
U.N. General Assembly's Resolution 2758 and the norms of
international law, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the Resolution 2758 passed by the U.N. General
Assembly in 1971 has resolved the issue of representation of China
in the U.N. in a just, thorough and comprehensive way, and Taiwan,
as a province of China, lacks qualification necessary for
U.N. membership.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan authorities' attempts to create "two Chinas" or "one
China, one Taiwan" in the U.N. can not gain support and are doomed
to failure, noted Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely advise that the countries concerned including
Nicaragua, in consideration of their long-term interest, not be
used by the Taiwan authorities again in their attempt to split
China, and not harm the sentiments of the Chinese people again by
standing in opposition to the vast majority of U.N. member states,
 which runs counter to the historical trend", said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that the just cause of the Chinese
government and people to safeguard the country's sovereignty and
integrity will continue to win the understanding and support from
the governments of most U.N. member states and people around the
world, " he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of China Offers Loan for Road Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China will grant
a loan of 625 million yuan to Tianjin to build an expressway,
according to an agreement signed here this week.
</P>
<P>
The investment for the construction of the road is 1.1 billion
yuan, which would be raised from firms in and out of China through
Hong Kong-based Peregrine Investment Holdings Ltd.
</P>
<P>
However, the part of investment to be raised from abroad did
not come after Peregrine went bankrupt in the wake of the Asian
financial crisis. And the project had to stop due to a lack of
funds. The bank decided to offer a helping hand after careful
investigations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yulan, a leading bank official, said the bank will
continue to offer loans for projects in the fields of
infrastructure, transportation and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The four-lane expressway will link downtown Tianjin with the
Tianjin Harbor and the Binhai District at a nearby development
zone. It will be able to accommodate 5,000-to-6,000 motor vehicles
an hour.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed in 2000, it will take half an
hour to travel between Tianjin's city proper and the development
zone, said a local government official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
