<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbani Asks Iran to Arm Refugees Against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's deposed
President Burhanuddin Rabbani has asked Iran to arm the Afghan
refugees in Iran to fight against the Taliban militia, local daily
Iran News reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily, Rabbani said that his
government expected Iran to provide proper facilities to the
Afghan refugees in Iran so that they would be able to return to
their country to join the "national-religious Jihad (holy war)
against the enemies of the country".
</P>
<P>
He did not reveal if Tehran accepted his demand. But local
observers said that the Iranian government is considering the
proposal as it has vowed to avenge the Taliban's killing of
several Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that nine Iranian diplomats working in its consulate
in Mazari Sharif, northern Afghanistan, were killed by the
Taliban on August 8 when the Taliban forces took over the city.
</P>
<P>
Iran said only two other Iranian diplomats succeeded in
escaping the massacre, while Taliban on Friday said that all the
11 Iranian diplomats were dead.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem is scheduled to
arrive here Saturday afternoon to consult with Iranian officials
about the latest development in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said that Cem's talks in Tehran would focus on
the joint efforts of Turkey and Iran to help Rabbani's government
prevent the Taliban from taking over whole Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Rabbani-led government was ousted in 1996, and the Taliban
forces have taken over most of the country. However, the
international community still considers Rabbani as the legitimate
ruler of the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the possibility of an armed conflict between the
Taliban and Iran, Rabbani stated that "it is the natural right of
any country to adopt defensive measures if that country's
territories are threatened."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that Iran had no intention to have a military
conflict with the Taliban, and Taliban's supporters should not do
anything which might deteriorate the situation. He was apparently
referring to Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and United Arab Emirates which
support and recognize the Taliban regime.
</P>
<P>
He also urged international bodies, the United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference in particular, to become
more actively involved in resolving the Afghan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Credit Rating Downgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- International credit
rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's has downgraded the outlook for
New Zealand's credit rating.
</P>
<P>
S&AMP;P affirmed this week its main AA+ long-term foreign currency
rating for New Zealand but changed the outlook to negative from
stable, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The ratings system has three levels: the outlook, which may be
positive, stable or negative; credit watch for a possible change
of rating; and the decision itself.
</P>
<P>
The downgrade absorbed the New Zealand government's latest
budget statement this week. The New Zealand Treasury in an
economic forecast predicted the country's economic growth of
negative 0.5 percent in the year to March 1999. It is also
forecast that the New Zealand government will have a deficit of
700 million NZ dollars in 1999-2000 and 300 million NZ dollars the
year after.
</P>
<P>
While downgrading the outlook for New Zealand's credit rating,
S&AMP;P cited uncertainty about New Zealand government's policy
because the National Party, the ruling party in the government,
lacks a secure parliamentary majority and might lose power in the
next election. It also cited proximity to East Asia's severe
recession, a deterioration in New Zealand government's budget and
persistent balance of payments pressures.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that rival agency Moody's Investor Services has
its AA1 rating of New Zealand under review for a possible
downgrade.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's credit rating is second behind AAA which applies
to only 12 countries out of 76 rated by S&AMP;P. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives for Border Area Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been making
efforts to develop the country's border areas since the present
government took over the state power in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The government has formed the Progress of Border Areas and
National Races and Development Affairs Ministry and the Central
Committee for Development of Border Areas and National Races to
help develop the economy, social conditions and transport of
border areas, while conserving the traditions and culture and
literature of nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government has increased investment in the border
areas' development projects.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the government has spent more
than 9.51 billion kyats (about 31.7 million U.S. dollars) so far
for the projects of building roads, bridges, hospitals,
dispensaries, schools, irrigation facilities, generators, TV
retransmission stations and communication links in the regions.
</P>
<P>
The government has also designated the 1998-99 fiscal year
which began in April as the year of roads and bridges to
facilitate road links among villages and the rural and the urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the development of the border areas, the
government also gives more priorities to controlling narcotic
drugs. Myanmar has been able to turn the Mongla region in eastern
Shan state into an opium-free zone and efforts are being made to
bring about more similar zones. The country plans to totally
eliminate poppy cultivation in 15 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
