<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Ministers Meeting on Congo Conflict Reaches No Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The three-day meeting of
defense ministers of seven African countries ended at 02:30 a.m.
(local time) Saturday, with no agreement reached on the
cease-fire and withdrawal of foreign troops from the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was attended by defense ministers of
Angola, the DRC, Rwanda, Namibia, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe as
well as officials and representatives of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations, was held in Addis
Ababa in accordance with the mandate given to it by the second
summit at Zimbabwe's Victoria Falls earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The task of the defense ministers meeting was to establish the
modalities for effecting an immediate cease-fire and a mechanism
for monitoring compliance with the cease-fire provisions,
especially those relating to the withdrawal of foreign forces
from the DRC.
</P>
<P>
After its opening session on Thursday afternoon, the meeting
entered closed session immediately. The ministers resumed
their meeting at 10:30 p.m. Friday to discuss the draft modalities
for a cease-fire agreement but their views were divergent on the
draft. The delegations from Rwanda and Uganda left the meeting
hall around 01:00 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued by OAU here on Saturday morning said:
"The ministers worked out draft modalities for a cease-fire
agreement in the DRC. The outcome of their deliberations will be
submitted to their respective governments."
</P>
<P>
"Considering that this is a continuing and intense process,"
the statement said that "more consultations need to be undertaken."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
