<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Growth Slows Down in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports and
imports in both baht and U.S. dollar terms recorded slower growth
in August compared with July, statistics of the Customs Department
showed.
</P>
<P>
In a report available Saturday, the Customs Department said
exports in August totaled 174.7 billion baht, down by 17.7 billion
baht or 9.22 percent from July. In dollar term, exports fell by
9.11 percent to 4.26 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports totaled 138 billion baht, down by 10.15 percent from
July, while the dollar value fell by 9.89 percent to 3.32 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 export items for the month were computers and parts,
electrical appliances, garments, rubber, electrical circuit boards
and parts, rice, canned seafood, plastic and products, gems and
jewelry, and vehicles and other automotive products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country saw a trade surplus of 36.74 billion
baht (91.85 million dollars) in August, which result in a total
surplus of 305.25 billion baht or 7.43 billion dollars for the
first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had trade surplus with the United States, the European
Union and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, but had a
deficit with Japan and other trading partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government has rejected the proposed
10 percent across-the-board import surcharge but agreed to study
selective imposition of the surcharge in a bid to mitigate the
adverse effects of the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government's inter-agency Economic Mobilization Group made
this decision at a meeting Friday, the Philippine Journal reported
Saturday. (Philippines-Import)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- The devalued New Zealand dollar has helped bump
up food prices in the local markets.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by Statistics New Zealand, the
New Zealand dollar fell 4.4 percent in the second quarter and
13.9 percent in the year ending June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The lower New Zealand dollar hits food prices in the local
markets, which rose 1.1 percent in August and were 4.2 percent
higher than a year ago. (New Zealand-Currency)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar plunged against the Japanese yen
Friday despite a report that Japan's economy slid even deeper into
recession in the April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
The mark swung wildly but recovered against the German currency
as U.S. stocks rallied late in the day.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell to a five-month low against the yen while
dropping to an 18-month low against the mark. The Mexican peso
edged down, falling to a new low against the dollar for the
seventh consecutive trading session. (New York-Dollar Plunges)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Light gains on Wall Street left European equity
markets not far from previous closes on Friday after registering
heavy falls in morning trade on growing concerns that
U.S. President Clinton could face impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
London blue chip shares climbed off the floor to show only
modest losses at the close, pulled up by Wall Street's opening
gains.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 finished the day 18 lower at 5118, on moderate
volume of 868m shares traded. (European Stocks-Rally)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Stocks on Wall Street rose sharply in volatile
trading Friday, with the Dow industrials up almost 180 points.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street found encouragement in corporate profitability
pronouncements that overcame fears surrounding global economic
strife and unease over the fate of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average leaped 179.96 points, or by
2.4 percent, to close at 7,795.50. It gained 155.25 for the week.
But the Dow still was 16.5 percent below the July 17 record of
9,337.97 and 1.4 percent below where it began the year. (New
York-Stocks Down)
</P>
