<HEADLINE> Foodstocks Enough, Stop Panic Buying: Bangladeshi PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina urged the people to refrain from panic buying of
rice, saying the foodstocks in the country are enough and imports
of sufficient amounts of rice have been made.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for worries, we have got sufficient stock
of rice and more foodgrains are in the pipeline from various
external sources to tackle any situation," she said while
addressing a rally held Friday in the southeast district of
Narayanganj, media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The government has made all arrangements for importing
required quantities of food, including rice," she told the
gathering, citing that some people in the capital had
unnecessarily gone on panic-buying of rice.
</P>
<P>
The government has already appealed to donors for aid and the
responses from different countries and agencies have been
positive, she added.
</P>
<P>
This year's flood has surpassed the records of the 1988 deluge
in terms of intensity and devastation, the prime minister
observed, saying that relief could not be reached everywhere as a
large number of roads have been damaged by flood.
</P>
<P>
However, she assured that relief supplies, including
foodstuffs, were being airdropped to the inaccessible, remote
areas.
</P>
<P>
The over two-month-long flood, which is still going on and
deteriorating further in a number of districts in the country, has
already affected over 30 million people in 47 districts of the
country's 64 districts, with the death toll rising to 843 so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
