<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Public Debt Stands at 40 Percent of GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's public debt stands
at 40 percent of gross domestic product (GDP), high by Thai
standards but low compared with that of developed countries, the
Bangkok Post said Saturday, quoting Fiscal Policy Office
Director-General Sommai Phasee.
</P>
<P>
Public debt of Thailand includes 500 billion baht (12.5 billion
U.S. dollars) in liabilities incurred by the Finance Institutions
Development Fund for its support of ailing banks and finance
companies in the past year, Sommai said.
</P>
<P>
The debt burden also includes 300 billion baht (7.5 billion
dollars) used for the government's financial reform and
recapitalization plan announced on August 14, as well as 5 billion
dollars to be issued in global bonds within a few years.
</P>
<P>
Sommai said Thailand's public debt is low compared with that of
Japan, which stood at 65 percent of its GDP, the United States at
70 percent, Britain 59 percent and Canada 118 percent.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that Finance Ministry officials met Friday
to discuss Thailand's foreign debt for fiscal 1998, which ends
this month.
</P>
<P>
The debt ceiling currently stands at 7.2 billion dollars,
excluding loans from the International Monetary Fund, the World
Bank and other assistance agencies.
</P>
<P>
Sommai said the foreign borrowing limit for the next fiscal
year would likely be maintained at this year's level or increased,
to help infrastructure development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central European Countries Agree to Help Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of 16 Central
European countries agreed on plans to aid Kosovo refugees in
Albania and help reconstruct the Albanian economy as they
concluded a two-day meeting here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The delegates, representing members of the Central European
Initiative Countries Organization (CEICO), decided to provide 500
dual-purpose stoves (for cooking and heating) worth 70,000
U.S. dollars for Kosovo refugees in Albania as winter approaches.
</P>
<P>
Italy announced that it will give some plank cabins to the
refugees while Slovenia will donate 140,000 marks (82,840 dollars)
through the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The delegates agreed to send a fact-finding group to look into
winter preparations in Kosovo refugee camps in Albania before a
forthcoming high-level CEICO meeting in Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
CEICO's efforts to shore up the Albanian economy include a plan
to improve the electricity grid in the capital city of Tirana, a
15-kilometer road project from Librazhd to Qukes and a revamp of
the Durres freight yard to a free tariff zone.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also decided to hold a high-level economic
meeting this year and establish direct links with European and
other regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
CEICO, set up in 1990 for closer cooperation in economic,
science, culture and political fields, consists of Albania,
Austria, Belarus, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech
Republic, Hungary, Italy, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania,
Slovakia, Slovenia and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
