<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel said in the city of Krakow Friday that
Germany stood on the side of Russia at this moment of crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with his Polish
counterpart Bronislaw Geremek, Kinkel said Yevgeny Primakov had
telephoned him on Thursday and said Russia would continue the
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia needed the help of western exports to solve
its economic crisis, and Germany was ready to offer its hands.
</P>
<P>
Geremek, the Polish foreign minister, said he hoped stability
would soon return to Russia after Primakov's nomination was
approved by the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel arrived in Krakow Friday to reward those who made
special contributions to Polish-Germany relations.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed the Kosovo situation.
They agreed that to end military actions by both sides and to have
peaceful dialogues were most important.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel added that both Poland and Germany supported Kosovo
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also promised to continue helping Poland become a
European Union member or member of other European
organizations. 
