<HEADLINE> Brazilian Stock Markets Register Strong Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sao Paulo and Rio de
Janeiro stock exchanges registered Friday gains of 13.39 and 11.6
percent at the close of their transactions, thanks to a strong
rise of the nation's interbank rate from the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, the biggest in Latin America,
registered 5,398 points and traded 524.8 million U.S. dollars,
while the Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange registered 18.412 points
and traded 58.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The strong gains were reported in the Brazilian stock markets
after they had registered Thursday record losses of 15.2 percent
and 15.9 percent respectively in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange president Alberto Reis said that
all this can be attributed mainly to the rise in the annual
interbank rate from the Central Bank of Brazil, announced late
Thursday night, which went from 29.75 percent to 49.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank had previously raised the interbank rate from
19 percent to 29.75 percent aiming at preventing speculative
operations and stopping the outflow of foreign currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
