<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Condemns Taliban for Murdering Iranian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada Friday condemned the
Taliban in Afghanistan for the murder of nine Iranian diplomats in
the Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"The killing of these Iranian officials demonstrates blatant
disregard of international law, and the Taliban cannot be excused for
its failure to control its soldiers," said Canadian Foreign Minister
Lloyd Axworthy in a release.
</P>
<P>
"Canada condemns these actions and any other forms of violence
against individuals in Afghanistan," added the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated Canada's support for the United Nations
Security Council's call for an urgent investigation into these
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy emphasized that "the Afghan crisis must be resolved by
peaceful means and that neighboring states must refrain from any
actions which could exacerbate the situation."
</P>
<P>
After having repeatedly denied any knowledge of their
whereabouts, the Taliban admitted Thursday that its military
forces had killed the missing Iranians. The Taliban leadership
claimed that its soldiers committed the murders on their own and
without any orders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Break Obstacles Run World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese women broke
the world record in the 500m obstacles run today here, sending
the host team to the top ranking in the CISM 46th Military
Pentathlon World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Shen Liping clocked two minutes 20.9 seconds, beating the
previous mark of 2:23.6 set by Denmark's Heidi Olsen last year in
Sweden and finishing first in the second day of the seven-day
competition.
</P>
<P>
Wen Yu started the record-breaking spree with a time of 2:23.1
and finished second, while four-time world champion Wang Lianying
ran at 2:23.4 for third.
</P>
<P>
China, who finished fourth yesterday after the shooting event,
took the lead in the women's team competition with 6,516.6
points, followed by Sweden with 6,310.1 and Denmark, 237.3 points
less than the leaders.
</P>
<P>
Wang took the leading place in the individual competition with
2,207.2 points after two disciplines, with Wu second on 2,196.7.
Liselotte Freuler of Switzerland was third with 2,151.2 points.
</P>
<P>
"I ran even faster in the training," Shen said. "But I have to
save the energy for the following competitions."
</P>
<P>
China's team leader Jiao Liming said: "I'm very happy but not
surprised because they've done it in the training. There's only
one regret that Wu Jinfeng, who ran the fastest in training,
didn't not finish the record-beating day."
</P>
<P>
Wu tumbled just before the finish and placed fourth with
2:24.9.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese are magnificent," Denmark coach Dennis Massesson
said. "Undoubtedly, they're the best." 
</P>
</TEXT>
