<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: S.Korea's Economic Sluggishness Deepens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean economy has
plunged into a deeper recession as gross domestic product (GDP)
and domestic consumption contracted sharply in the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The poor economic performance was blamed for a sharp fall in
both consumption and facility investment in the wake of the
financial turmoil, said the Bank of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Deepening sluggishness in domestic demand has gloomed the
prospects of the country's early economic recovery as economic
indicators related to production, consumption and investment
showed extremely poor results last month.
</P>
<P>
The nation has seen negative economic growth for seven months
in a row since January this year when output growth nosedived to
minus 10.8 percent from three percent last December.
</P>
<P>
Under a report on last month's industrial activity released by
the National Statistics Office, industrial production dived 12.9
percent in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Korea said in a report that the
country's economy sank by 6.4 percent in the first half of this
year while the GNP contracted by five percent and 7.6 percent in
the first and second quarters respectively, the worst setback in
the past 45 years.
</P>
<P>
Household consumption fell 11.9 percent due to wage cuts and
mass layoffs while facility investment plummeted 46.7 percent from
a year before.
</P>
<P>
Although the nation's export rose 20.9 percent, analysts warned
that export grow rate will decline for the rest of this year as
imports plummeted 23.7 percent in the first six months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The production of motor vehicles fell 45.4 percent in July from
a year earlier, partly affected by labor strike at Hyundai Motor
Corporation while output of machinery equipment and assembled
metals plunged 39.5 and 29.7 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Rapidly cooling domestic demand arising form pay cuts and
layoffs was the key reason behind weakening industrial activity in
the first half of 1998, said the Ministry of Finance and Economy.
</P>
<P>
Producers inventory contracted 7.8 percent in July as makers of
automobiles, machinery equipment and other domestic
demand-oriented goods trimmed production in the face of poor
domestic sales while wholesale and retail sales dropped 17.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The economic slump has become increasingly aggravated as
domestic demand has been sliding steeply due to plunging
consumption and investment as well as a slowdown in exports of
South Korean goods," said Lee Seong-tae, director of the research
department of the central Bank of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Economists predicted that the economy will deteriorate in the
second half of this year as there is no sign of improvement.
</P>
<P>
They said exports, a long-time locomotive for South Korea's
rapid economic growth, is expected to dwindle in the second six
months of this year due to the weakening Asian markets and
decreasing import of material.
</P>
<P>
Government officials predicted that the economy will shrink
seven percent this year while some even forecast that the GDP
growth rate will be a negative 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government announced last week a package of
monetary and fiscal measures to revitalize the rapidly cooling
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The package includes taking a flexible approach toward money
supply, expanding credit guarantees for small and mediumed sized
enterprises, exporters and housing builders and increasing
consumer financing instruments for buyers of houses and other
durable goods.
</P>
<P>
This package apparently came in response to a mounting fear
that the economy was dragged into deeper water by austere measures
imposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) last December,
when the nation signed an agreement with monetary body for a resue
loan of 58 billion U.S. dollars after suffering a financial crisis
caused by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial
institutions late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
