<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 40 in Mexico's Chiaps State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The biggest rainstorm in
Mexico within 40 years swept its southern state of Chiapas,
killing at least 40 people, victimizing more than 50,000 people
and causing enormous damage, the National Water Commission (CNA)
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, during the past 10 days, most areas in
the state were hit by a rainfall of 926.2 millimeters with daily
rainfall in some provinces reaching 341.9 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
The rains caused mountain torrents, mud-rock flows and floods,
which destroyed many villages, towns, roads and bridges, and cut
off regional communication and electricity in many localities.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon has inspected
some affected areas and helped direct the rescue work. Huge amount
of relief materials and rescue workers have been sent to the
afflicted areas.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring country Guatemala allowed Mexican rescuing vehicles
to pass its border freely.
</P>
<P>
Mexican ecologists said vast destruction of vegetation was one
of the causes of the rainstorms. From 1976 to 1991, 905,000
hectares of vegetation in Chiapas have been destroyed, which
cleared the way for the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
