<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President on Jaffna Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga said Friday the bomb that killed Jaffna
Mayor was targeted not only at him but also at the whole Tamil
community.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a press release issued Friday night that
the death of Jaffna Mayor Ponnuthurai Sivapalan, several army and
police officers and civilians in a bomb explosion earlier Friday
in Jaffna city has shocked all those who cherish peace.
</P>
<P>
The release said: "civil administration was restored in Jaffna
soon after the return of civilians who placed their confidence in
the government which liberated Jaffna city from the LTTE
terrorists. The government also held local elections in the city
and gave the people an opportunity to elect their own
representatives."
</P>
<P>
The president said what else have the Tigers done except
betraying the Tamil people by exploding bombs at a time when the
government is doing everything possible to develop Jaffna and
create a peaceful environment for its citizens who have undergone
untold hardships under the Tigers control?
</P>
<P>
In the release, she also said the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) which purports to represent the Tamil community has
bared its terrorist inclinations by attacking all sections of the
community.
</P>
<P>
All those who value peace and humanity reject the acts of
terror perpetrated by the LTTE, said she, adding that "I am
certain that the government will receive the support of all
sections of the community to achieve its noble objectives."
</P>
<P>
Jaffna city was once the stronghold of the LTTE rebels, who
have been fighting a 15-year war for a separate state in the
country. The city was recaptured by Sri Lankan government troops
in December, 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
