<HEADLINE> Divers Find Swissair Voice Cockpit Recorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Divers recovered Friday the
voice cockpit recorder of Swissair Flight 111 which crashed off
Canada's east coast last week, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The recorder is expected to help investigators know what
happened in the final moments of the jet crash, which killed all
229 passengers and crew aboard.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss plane, en route from New York to Geneva, crashed
about 60 kilometers southwest of Halifax, last Wednesday, about 16
minutes after the pilots reported smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
So far, experts are still trying to determine what caused the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The other so-called "black box", the inflight data recorder,
was recovered last Saturday, and sent to a lab here for analysis.
</P>
<P>
But experts found that an electrical failure moments before the
crash kept it from recording below from 10,000 feet, which was
about six minutes before the crash.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that the second recorder will shed some light on
what was going on in the cockpit in the last few minutes before
the crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
