<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian agricultural
delegation is visiting here to strengthen agricutural trade ties
between Canada and Mexico, a newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is composed of Minister of Agriculture Lyle
Vanclief, five provincial agricultural ministers and a group of
Canadian business leaders.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the visit is aimed to increase agricultural
trade with Mexico within the framework of North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
The two-way trade now stands at over 800 million U.S. dollars
and is expected to grow steadily.
</P>
<P>
Canada's agriculture and agri-food sector earns over 22 billion
dollars annually, comprising just under 9 percent of Canada's
Gross Domestic Product(GDP).
</P>
<P>
"Canada understands the benefits of partnering -- greater export
sales, cost savings, control of quality and enhanced economic
activity for both partners," the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived here on Thursday following a visit to
Brazil and Chile. 
