<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Once-Jailed Chinese Poet Views Honor as Token of Friendship (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- When Lu Yuan learned last
month of the decision to present him this year's Golden Wreath
Award of the Struga Poetry Evenings, he said: "This reflects the
friendship between the Chinese people and the Macedonian people."
</P>
<P>
Like most traditional Chinese scholars, the 76-year-old Chinese
poet, writer and translator who was once jailed for seven years
because of a false charge has serenity in the face of great honor.
</P>
<P>
On Aug. 23, he received the only Golden Wreath Award for this
year in the city of Struga in Macedonia, making him the first
Chinese who has won this renowned and long-standing prize in the
world's poetry circle.
</P>
<P>
The Struga Poetry Evenings, which started 37 years ago, is one
of the most important international gatherings held in Macedonia,
whose top prize -- the Golden Wreath Award -- is supposed to be
presented only to the world's most famous poets.
</P>
<P>
"Receiving such a prize is not only my personal glory, but also
the pride of the Chinese culture and, more important, it is a
reflection of the Macedonian people's friendship to the Chinese
people," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Struga Poetry Evenings as a contribution of the
Macedonian people to the world's cultural exchange, Lu said that
when more Chinese poems are understood by the world, the distance
between China and the world will become less.
</P>
<P>
"Through the efforts of poets, critics and translators, gaps
between different peoples will be bridged," he said.
</P>
<P>
On this year's Struga Poetry Evenings he recited one recent
work named "Chinese Kite": "...fly, fly up, higher and higher,
Chinese kite/ no matter how big universe gravity/ took you about
from all directions/ just thanks to an invisible, uncuttable,
umbilical cord/ connect you tightly with mother earth/ you are
unbeded forever in the childhood sky/ with the manner of
mysterious piece of brocade."
</P>
<P>
"In this poem one can read my love, feeling and thinking about
my own country", Lu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Once-Jailed Chinese Poet Views Honor as Token of Friendship (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that the reason he selected this piece to recite was
that it also deeply touched his many Macedonian friends.
</P>
<P>
"Paskal Gilevski, president of the Council of Struga Poetry
Evenings, once told me that they hope more Chinese kites, with
friendship, fly in the skies of Macedonia," Lu said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
After communicating with poets from more than 40 countries, Lu
said he found that Chinese poems, both traditional and modern,
have gained increasing understanding.
</P>
<P>
"Quite a lot of people know something about Qu Yuan, Li Ba and
many other famous Chinese poets," he said.
</P>
<P>
One thing Lu said deeply impressed him is that during the
recitation of his works Macedonia's 81-year-old president Kiro
Gligorov always sat quietly listening, although it was late at
night.
</P>
<P>
Lu was an English teacher in his early years. After New China
was founded in 1949, he worked for a newspaper. From 1955 to 1962,
he was jailed because he was believed to have had "different and
dangerous art values."
</P>
<P>
While jailed, he studied German and, when he was set free in
1962, he mastered the language so well that even some first-class
experts on German expressed surprise.
</P>
<P>
He worked mainly as a translator after 1962, but his isolation
lasted until 1980 when he was rehabilitated. Despite those hard
times, Lu Yuan has published 17 collections of poetry and 25 books
or translations.
</P>
<P>
"I have no time to regret the past; I need more time to write,
to think and to do my job better," Lu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0179 </DOCNO>
