<HEADLINE> Homes to Be Rebuilt for the Homeless in Flood Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- All efforts are being made to
ensure housing for people in China's flood-striken areas as winter
approaches, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
In Heilongjiang Province, where the swelling Nenjiang and
Songhuajiang rivers took away the homes of 900,000 people, the
government has vowed to ensure that residents are able to spend
the winter safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
"The top priority of our relief work is to see no one die from
the frigid winter temperatures," said Wang Donghua, vice-governor
of Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
The province has distributed 140 million yuan worth of relief
materials among flood victims to help them prepare for the coming
winter.
</P>
<P>
In Gannan County, the government has raised 600,000 yuan in
special housing funds to help the affected farmers set up new
housing by cutting daily expenditure and collecting donations.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Yunxiang, vice-governor of the county, the
government was giving thorough consideration to the design of new
scientific and flood-proof housing for more than 50,000 homeless
residents, most of who still live in public houses or the homes of
their relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
In Tailai, many homeless families have been given bricks to
build partial underground houses common in Northeast China.
</P>
<P>
In central China's Hubei Province, the provincial government
has outlined a package of construction plans, and new housing for
victims is expected to complete by the end of November.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, say it will take years to complete the home
reconstruction work and restore agriculture and industry in vast
hard-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
"We need about three years to make up for the heavy losses,"
said Liu Haisheng, Qiqihar mayor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
