<HEADLINE> Italy Condemns Assassination of Iranian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini sent a massage on Friday to his Iranian counterpart
Kamal Kharrazi condemning the assassination of Iranian diplomats
captured by Afghan Taleban Militias.
</P>
<P>
"I hope those responsible for the assassination will be soon
identified and called upon to take responsibility for a crime
committed in flagrant violation of current international
conventions and of the most fundamental principles of civil
coexistence," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
But Dini also said that while his condemnation of the
"barbarous crime" was firm, he hoped a sense of responsibility and
moderation would prevail to overcome the currently strained
relations between Iran and Afghanistan and to prevent an
escalation of hostilities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the 11 Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan were abducted
early last month after Taleban, who control most part of
Afghanistan, captured the northern Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif
from rival forces on August 8. There was no word about the fate of
two other diplomats who remained missing.
</P>
<P>
Taleban spokesman Maulvi Wakil Ahmed announced that the bodies
of the nine were found Wednesday in a mountain.
</P>
<P>
The Taleban militia on Thursday pledged to punish some of its
fighters who, "acting on their own", killed the nine Iranian
diplomats without orders.
</P>
<P>
But the government of Iran believed that Taleban should be
responsible for the crime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
