<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Mulls Selective Import Surcharge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
rejected the proposed 10 percent across-the-board import surcharge
but agreed to study selective imposition of the surcharge in a bid
to mitigate the adverse effects of the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government's inter-agency Economic Mobilization Group made
this decision at a meeting Friday, the Philippine Journal reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Undersecretary Ernesto Ordonez, a member of
the group, noted that when the country's tariffs were reduced
considerably the currency crisis was not yet raging.
</P>
<P>
But with the lingering financial crisis, the private sector has
clamored for a government measure that will dampen imports to help
local industries.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to impose a 10-percent surcharge on imported goods
was raised by business leaders during a recent joint Export
Development Council and Industry Development Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is intended to curtail the influx of imported
items and encourage local sourcing to assist local manufacturers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
