<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Farmers Turn to Accept One-Child Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers used to
believe that "a cluster of children stand for happiness," but now
many young rural couples choose to have only one child.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zhijun, a farmer in Xinle City of north China's Hebei
Province, has five siblings but he decided to have no more
children after his own daughter was born three years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said he was deeply aware of the burden of too many children
on society as well as on his family. As his family could not
afford to build another house, he had to live with his parents and
younger sister in the same room until he was 18 years old. "I
don't want to follow my parents," he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the natural population growth rate in
China has declined from 2.58 percent in 1970 to 1.055 percent in
1995 due to the implementation of the "one-child" birth control
policy. The decline has delayed China's population growth, and
otherwise the figure would have reached 1.2 billion nine years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Xie Daomin, a Chinese expert, said that the achievement should
be attributed to the consciousness of common people, especially to
the 800 million people in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Farmers -- not only among the Han people, but also among ethnic
groups -- have realized the significance of birth control.
</P>
<P>
Yangjim, a resident of Drashi Village of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, decided to have no more children after having a child. She
said that a mother with fewer children can retain her vigor
although ethnic minorities are allowed to have more children in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it is the development of the rural economy that
changes the old birth idea of Chinese farmers. Many young farmers
are occupied with their economic operations, so they are reluctant
to be worn out by having more than one child.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the improving social security system has created
favorable conditions for birth control as farmers gradually have
fewer worries about their pensions.
</P>
<P>
To date, 82 million rural residents in China have bought
pension insurance.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Chinese Ministry of Civil Affairs said that
China is expected to set up a countryside insurance system in 20
years. And it will help more Chinese farmers to accept a one-child
family, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
