<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Pace up Road Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China plans to beef up the
construction of roads and railways to sustain economic growth,
especially in the wake of recent floods.
</P>
<P>
According to incomplete statistics from the Ministry of
Communications, the floods had damaged 46 State level and 483
provincial-level highways and 2,393 county roads to varying
degrees.
</P>
<P>
Some 29,000 km of roads have been damaged, about 2.5 percent of
the country's total.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard the transportation of relief materials, the
ministry has earmarked 60 million yuan for repairs to the damaged
roads.
</P>
<P>
Despite the huge losses caused by the floods, the ministry is
determined to fulfill the target it set earlier this year, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways also plans to readjust its
construction schedule in an effort to do more to expand internal
demand and stimulate economic growth in the remaining four months.
</P>
<P>
Railway construction in the past few months has been slower
than expected due to a lack of preparatory work.
</P>
<P>
Major problems have arisen in acquiring the land required for
building the lines.
</P>
<P>
These problems have been compounded by the prolonged flooding
in certain areas of the country since June.
</P>
<P>
In spite of flood damage and the abnormally high temperatures
this year in some parts of the country, the ministry completed
investment of 10.37 billion yuan from June to August.
</P>
<P>
The State recently decided to increase investment in the sector
by 4.2 billion yuan to give further stimulus to railway
development.
</P>
<P>
Adding in funds from local authorities and foreign investors,
investment in the sector this year is expected to reach 53 billion
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
