<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine expects little "special
change" in its relations with a Russian government led by new
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing is for Primakov's appointment to
benefit Russia, Kuchma told reporters during a visit to Kiev's
Polytechnic University.
</P>
<P>
"What benefits Russia will benefit Ukraine," he stressed,
affirming that his country hopes for an early restoration of
political stability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said he would meet Russian President Boris
Yeltsin as planned on September 18-19 but the meeting place is
being rearranged.
</P>
<P>
"We have not yet decided (the place of the meeting)," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a previous plan, business leaders and regional
representatives were allowed to attend the meeting, scheduled in
Kharkov in eastern Ukraine close to the Russia border, for talks
on state issues and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Noting that trade and transactions have been temporarily
suspended between Ukraine and Russia, Kuchma said that "it is
necessary today to have a summit" to coordinate actions.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ukrainian side needs to know more about Moscow's
views and opinions after its cabinet reshuffle. 
