<HEADLINE> Air Transportation Expanding in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Three Airbus 340 passenger
jets will be delivered to China Southwest Airlines in Chengdu next
month, the first jumbo jets in the airline's fleet.
</P>
<P>
The deal for 360 million U.S. dollars is part of the airline's
strategic investment program to compete in the rapidly growing air
transportation market in China, according to Zhou Zhengquan,
director of Civil Aviation Administration of China's Southwestern
Branch.
</P>
<P>
He said that both Yunnan and Guizhou Airlines also plan to
purchase planes abroad, with Guizhou cooperating with China
Southern Airlines to import two Boeing passenger jets this year.
</P>
<P>
Southwestern China includes Sichuan, Yunnan, and Guizhou
provinces, as well as Chongqing municipality and the Tibet
Autonomous Region. Due to the rough terrain and difficult land
communications in this area, air transportation is growing by 30
percent on an average annual basis.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, there were only 20 passenger planes and eight civil
airports in this region, but the numbers are expected to climb to
70 and 19, respectively, by the end of this year and to 200 and 40
in 2010, Zhou said. enditem
