<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis, Novotna into U.S. Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The No. 1 player in the
world and the top player this summer will meet in the U.S. Open
women's singles final.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Martina Hingis rallied from two service
breaks down in the third set today to beat doubles partner Jana
Novotna 3-6, 6-1, 6-4, and earn a berth opposite second seed
American Lindsay Davenport in Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, who won three titles during the summer season,
gained her first Grand Slam final by disposing of fellow American
Venus Williams 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Hingis won 18 of the final 22 points to overcome Novotna's 4-1
advantage in the deciding set and protect the world top spot she
has held for the last 76 weeks. Had she lost today, the
17-year-old would have surrendered the place to Davenport.
</P>
<P>
"I was just fighting," Hingis said of the comeback. "It was
getting windy and I was trying to keep the ball in the game. I
also wanted to protect my No. 1 ranking."
</P>
<P>
The loss was a disappointing one for the third-seeded Novotna.
After years of missed opportunities in big matches, the
29-year-old shed the "choker" tag by winning Wimbledon this year.
But the label is sure to return after her shaky performance in
the final two sets today and her collapse in the final five games.
</P>
<P>
A service break in the opening game of the third set gave
Novotna early control and a forehand winner and overhead smash
gave her another break and a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
But Hingis regrouped and broke Novotna three consecutive times
while twice holding serve at love. A backhand passing shot and a
backhand winner up the line gave Hingis two match points.
</P>
<P>
She sent a lob over the baseline on her first opportunity, but
cashed in and earned her sixth Grand Slam final when Novotna
netted a forehand on the next point.
</P>
<P>
"I was up 4-1 and from that moment on I started to miss too
many approach shots and volleys," Novotna said. "Against a player
like Martina you can't do that. I was simply missing too many
ball."
</P>
<P>
Novotna, the aggressor throughout, committed 50 unforced errors
 in the match, 20 in the final set. She made 17 unforced errors
and managed only 14 points in the second set, which Hingis won in
only 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Everything started to go too fast for me in the second set,"
said Novotna, who held serve to open the set and then dropped the
next six games. "I just lost it very easily."
</P>
<P>
Hingis will be gunning for her fifth Grand Slam singles title
and first singles title of any kind in early four months in
Saturday's final. She won the Australian Open, Wimbledon and U.
S. Open in 1997, and defending her Australian Open title earlier
this year. She has won three other tournaments this year, but
none since the Italian Open in early May.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, appearing in her fourth semifinal in the last five
Grand Slams, simply overpowered the hard-hitting Williams. Her
penetrating groundstrokes kept the fifth seed pinned at or behind
the baseline for much of the match. Williams made 26 unforced
errors.
</P>
<P>
"She was stepping into her balls well," said Williams. "She's
one of the more powerful players on the tour."
</P>
<P>
"I think she wasn't going for her shots as much, trying to be
consistent," said Davenport, who is coming off a summer season
which included three consecutive wins. "It was giving me a little
bit more time to set up and I knew if I had the opportunity I
really had to go for the shot. I was able to do that."
</P>
<P>
Davenport jumped out to a 3-0 lead in the opening set with a
pair of service breaks, but watched as Williams pulled even just
as quickly. After three additional service breaks, Davenport held
to take the set.
</P>
<P>
"I had all types of opportunities, just a matter of
capitalizing on them," Williams said of the first set. "I think
she did a better job of that today. She was more consistent and
ready to win."
</P>
<P>
The second set was the complete opposite as each player
controlled play on their serve. Davenport cashed in on the only
break point of the set in the seventh game to take a 4-3 lead and
served out the match, losing only one point in her final two
service games.
</P>
<P>
"At 5-4, I was just trying to be calm and tell myself to serve
a good game, " said Davenport, who wrapped up the match when
Williams sent a return past the baseline. "I knew the return was
going long and it was relief, it was happiness, it was joy obviou
sly getting to my first final."
</P>
<P>
Saturday's final will be the fourth meeting between Hingis and
Davenport this year. Davenport has won two of the previous three,
including the last meetings in the Los Angeles final, but Hingis
leads the all-time series 6-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
