<HEADLINE> Jones, Thompson Steal Show in Athletics World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Marion Jones of the
United States and Obadele Thompson of Barbados stole the show at
the first day of the 8th International Amateur Athletics
Federation World Cup on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jones broke the women's 200 meters World Cup record of 21.83
seconds by finishing at 21.62 seconds. Thompson set a new World
Cup record in men's 100 meters with 9.87 seconds.
</P>
<P>
African athletes grabbed the first two golds in Friday's
competition. Nezha Bidouane from Morocco snatched the first gold
for the African contingent in the women's 400m hurdles with 52.96
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Samuel Matete won the second gold for Africa when
he took the lead in the men's 400m hurdles and finished 48.08
seconds. He was followed by Asia's Mubarak Al-Nubi, who clocked
48.17s, and Jamaican Dinsdale Morgan, with 48.40s.
</P>
<P>
Top athletes from around the globe began competing for their
continents as the Athletics World Cup opened on Friday afternoon
in Johannesburg, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The biggest commercial metropolis in southern Africa welcomed
the world athletics event with a refreshing shower, which has
been absent in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Teams of both sexes from five continents and two sports
superpowers-- the United States and Germany -- and an additional
men's team from Britain and a women's team from Russia, will
contest for the team trophy of the event, which was recently
renamed Nelson Mandela Trophy.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day competition, over 400 elite athletes will
take part in 20 men's events and 17 women' events. The medalists
will, for the first time in the 21 years' history of the World
Cup, get cash rewards ranging from 50,000 U.S. dollars to 10,000
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The men's contingents from Africa and the United States are
among the favorites for this year's World Cup, and the women's
teams from the United States and Europe are also hopeful for
claiming the title. In the 1994 World Cup, Africa won the trophy
in the men's events and Europe won in the women's.
</P>
<P>
The Asian contingent, which is significantly represented by
Chinese, also vowed to do their best in the contest. Twenty-three
of the team's 55 athletes are from China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
