<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devalued New Zealand Dollar Hits Food Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The devalued New Zealand
dollar has helped bump up food prices in the local markets.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by Statistics New Zealand, the
New Zealand dollar fell 4.4 percent in the second quarter and
13.9 percent in the year ending June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The lower New Zealand dollar hits food prices in the local
markets, which rose 1.1 percent in August and were 4.2 percent
higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The monthly rise was the largest since May 1995 and the annual
rise was the largest since September 1990, Statistics New Zealand
said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest influences were a 7.2 percent rise in the price of
milk, a 24.4 percent rise in the price of cauliflower and rises in
imported grocery prices.
</P>
<P>
"The falling New Zealand dollar has been reflected in higher
import prices for foodstuffs and higher prices for meat and dairy
exports in the June 1998 quarter (the second quarter of the year).
This may well have contributed to this month's (August) sharp
increase in the food price index," deputy government statistician
Ian Ewing was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
When export prices rise, local prices tend to rise to match
them. A lower New Zealand dollar makes the price of imported goods
higher, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
