<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Beat Novotna to Enter U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Martina Hingis of
Switzerland came back one set down to beat Jana Novotna of the
Czech Republic in the semifinal of the U.S. Open tennis
championships here today.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Hingis secured her No. 1 ranking with the
victory when she beat the world number two player 3-6, 6-1, 6-4.
She will face American Lindsay Davenport in Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
Hingis won 18 of the final 22 points to overcome Novotna's 4-1
advantage in the deciding set and protect the world top spot she
has held for the last 76 weeks. Had she lost today, the
17-year-old would have surrendered the place to Davenport.
</P>
<P>
"I was just fighting," Hingis said of the comeback. "It was
getting windy and I was trying to keep the ball in the game. I
also wanted to protect my No. 1 ranking."
</P>
<P>
The loss was a disappointing one for the third-seeded Novotna.
After years of missed opportunities in big matches, the
29-year-old shed the "choker" tag by winning Wimbledon this year.
But the label is sure to return after her shaky performance in
the final two sets today and her collapse in the final five games.
</P>
<P>
A service break in the opening game of the third set gave
Novotna early control and a forehand winner and overhead smash
gave her another break and a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
But Hingis regrouped and broke Novotna three consecutive times
while twice holding serve at love. A backhand passing shot and a
backhand winner up the line gave Hingis two match points.
</P>
<P>
She sent a lob over the baseline on her first opportunity, but
cashed in and earned her sixth Grand Slam final when Novotna
netted a forehand on the next point.
</P>
<P>
"I was up 4-1 and from that moment on I started to miss too
many approach shots and volleys," Novotna said. "Against a player
like Martina you can't do that. I was simply missing too many
ball."
</P>
<P>
Novotna, the aggressor throughout, committed 50 unforced
errors in the match, 20 in the final set. She made 17 unforced
errors and managed only 14 points in the second set, which Hingis
won in only 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Everything started to go too fast for me in the second set,"
said Novotna, who held serve to open the set and then dropped the
next six games. "I just lost it very easily."
</P>
<P>
Hingis will be gunning for her fifth Grand Slam singles title a
nd first singles title of any kind in early four months in
Saturday's final. She won the Australian Open, Wimbledon and U.S.
Open in 1997, and defending her Australian Open title earlier
this year. She has won three other tournaments this year, but
none since the Italian Open in early May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Moves into U.S. Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Lindsay
Davenport of the United States ousted her compatriot Venus
Williams 6-4, 6-4 to advance to the women's singles final of the
U.S. Open tennis championships here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old will battle against Martina Hingis of
Switzerland in Saturday's showdown. Davenport, who won three
titles during the summer season, gained her first Grand Slam
final in commanding style.
</P>
<P>
She jumped out to a 3-0 lead in the opening set with a pair of
service breaks, but the number 5 seed Williams pulled it even
quickly. After three additional service breaks, Davenport held to
take the set.
</P>
<P>
The second set was the complete opposite as each player
controlled play in their serve. Davenport cashed in on the only
break point of the set in the seventh game to take a 4-3 lead,
and from then, she surged ahead, losing only one point in her
final two service games.
</P>
<P>
Williams brought seven dresses to the Open, one for each round
on the road to the finals, but she got no chance to wear the last
dress.
</P>
<P>
"I'm deeply saddened. I didn't have an opportunity to wear my
seventh dress," Williams said. "It was red, white and blue. Of
course matching hair and nails. I'm definitely going to put that
one in a coffin and bury it."
</P>
<P>
Williams, who reached the finals in her first appearance last
year at the Open, said: "I had all types of opportunities. It was
a matter of capitalizing on them. She did a better job of that.
She was more consistent and ready to win."
</P>
<P>
Williams, just 18 and in her second full year on the pro tour,
was critical of her performance.
</P>
<P>
"I really have to work hard on being better. I think I'm
pretty solid. I just have to become a better player, make better
decisions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
