<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs Chairman "Turns down Preliminary Offer" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tottenham Hotspur chairman
Alan Sugar turned down an 80 million pounds (135 million U.S.
dollars) offer for his English premier league club because it is
too low, according to local reports here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sugar, who is keen to sell his 40 percent stake in Spurs,
reportedly turned down the "indicative offer" from investment
company ENIC, which also has a stake in Rangers in Scotland, AEK
Athens in Greece, Vicenza in Italy and Slavia Prague in the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
ENIC has reportedly not made a formal bid for Spurs, which in
1983 became the first soccer club to be quoted on the London
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Neither Tottenham nor ENIC would comment on the report, which
follows a frenzy of activity in soccer clubs this week with
Manchester United agreeing a 624 million pounds (one billion U.S.
dollars) deal with BSkyB, Arsenal being courted by Carlton
Communications in a 275.0 million pounds (464 million U.S.
dollars) deal and Aston Villa also reportedly talking to media
organizations about possible future co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday Liverpool, who were linked with a possible
takeover by another broadcasting company, denied any chance of a
takeover.
</P>
<P>
Tottenham's value has been put at around 65 million pounds
(109.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sugar's personal stake in Tottenham is valued at around 32.0
million pounds (54 million U.S. dollars), almost three times the
amount he invested in the club when he took control in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Sugar announced two weeks ago he wanted to sell his
controlling interest in Tottenham because of the abuse he has
received from fans unhappy at the club's lack of success since he
took over seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
They have not won a trophy since the F.A. Cup in 1991, just
before he took control, and have had more managers -- six -- in
the last seven years than they had in the previous three decades.
</P>
<P>
Tottenham, traditionally one of the biggest and most
successful clubs in English soccer, has fallen behind the
standards set by Manchester United, Chelsea and Arsenal in the
last few seasons.
</P>
<P>
The club, eighth in the premier league, are currently looking
for a new coach after Sugar sacked Swiss Christian Gross after 10
unhappy months last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Although Tottenham have not challenged for honors for some
time, they have a successful pedigree in Europe, having won the
European Cup Winners' Cup in 1963 and the UEFA Cup in 1972 and
1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
