<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Opposes Inclusion of Question of Taiwan's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Resolution of the
General Assembly 2758 (XXVI) adopted in 1971 stated unequivocally
that the representatives of the Government of the People's Republic
of China are the sole and lawful representatives of China to the
United Nations and this resolution is still valid today, Tanzania
stressed here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the General Committee of the 53rd Session of the
General Assembly, Daudi Mwakawago, Tanzania's Ambassador to the
United Nations, said this resolution restored all rights of the
the People's Republic of China at the United Nations and any
attempt to inscribe the question of the so called "Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations" will be clearly the
interference of China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mwakawago said Tanzania believes that the resolution 2758
showed the General Assembly's respect for the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the People's Republic of China and
domestic issues of one country can only be solved by peaceful
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said any attempt by the international
community aimed to discuss such issues should be fully
discouraged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0212 </DOCNO>
