<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPU Conference Concludes in Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The 100th Conference of the
Inter- Parliamentary Union (IPU) ended Friday in the Kremlin after
adopting three resolutions on human rights, water resources and
the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
During much of the six-day event, people's attention was drawn
to what was happening to the political scene of host Russia.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the close of the IPU conference, acting foreign
minister Yevgeny Primakov was confirmed in the State Duma, or
lower house of parliament, as Russia's new prime minister, the
third in less than six months.
</P>
<P>
The resolution on the intensification of activities of national
parliaments in ensuring and defending human rights in the 21st
century was adopted in connection with the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The conference recommended to governments and parliaments to
promote the abolition of the death penalty, tortures and inhumane
treatment of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
China made reservations concerning the abolition of death
penalty and stipulations for the international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
The conference also recommended to governments and parliaments
to mark March 8, 2000, as a day of peace, development and
democracy based on the growing role of women.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution on water resources, the conference called
for measures for the preservation, distribution and optimal use of
such resources to ensure stable development.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, nominated by President Boris Yeltsin mid-Thursday,
delivered a speech before the world parliamentarians hours later,
noting that his country, though "temporarily feeble internally"
remains a major power in world affairs.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State Duma, was one of the
busiest, if not the busiest, inside the Garden Ring of Moscow.
Besides chairing the open and closed sessions in the IPU
conference, he also had to chair sessions in the State Duma, not
to say the political bargaining outside the Duma building centered
around the nomination of premier.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, who was chairman of the conference, said the
gathering "turned out to be quite in time" despite the fact that
the conference coincided with the country's political and economic
crises.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the parliamentarians for their support and assured
them that the State Duma would always be a "factor of democracy
and a guarantor that no more revolutionary coups will occur in
Russia".  
</P>
</TEXT>
