<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Plunges Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar plunged
against the Japanese yen Friday despite a report that Japan's
economy slid even deeper into recession in the April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
The mark swung wildly but recovered against the German currency
as U.S. stocks rallied late in the day.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell to a five-month low against the yen while
dropping to an 18-month low against the mark. The Mexican peso
edged down, falling to a new low against the dollar for the
seventh consecutive trading session.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar closed at worth 130.82 yen, down from
134.23 yen late Thursday. During trading, the dollar fell to
129.00 yen, a level last seen on April 10.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency also rose to 1.6935 marks, up from 1.6843,
but that came after an intraday decline to 1.6708 marks, a level
last seen on April 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico City, the dollar was worth a record 10.6050 pesos, up
from 10.6000. In late trading in New York, the dollar was trading
at 10.5400, up from 10.4000 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets worldwide fell Friday, with slight drops in
European exchanges and a 5.1 percent plunge in Tokyo's Nikkei Stock
Average.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.3890 Swiss francs, up from 1.3845; 5.6790 French
francs, up from 5.6565; 1,672.00 Italian lire, up from 1,663.30;
and 1.5129 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5160.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6728 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6895 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
