<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Agrees to Compensate War-Time Forces Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest carmaker
Volkswagen AG announced Friday that it has decided to set up a
private fund to provide humanitarian relief to individuals who
were forced to work for the company during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The fund will have a budget of 20 million German marks (12
million U.S. dollars) with the first payments due to be made
within this year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen estimatedly employed between 15,000 to 20,000 slave
laborers during the Nazi era, including about 1,500 Jewish people
between period from 1944 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
A number of other large German companies also employed slave
laborers during World War II and have faced increasing pressure to
pay individual compensation. Volkswagen is the first one to take
concrete actions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
