<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Urged to Give up Illusions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese
diplomat on Friday urged the Taiwan authorities to give up any
illusion because the island, an inalienable part of China, has no
qualification for the membership of the United Nations, an
intergovernmental body composed of sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, voiced his hope that "The Taiwan authorities should
realize that it has no qualification for and no possibility to the
membership of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"Now it is time for the Taiwan authorities to give up any
illusions and nobody on earth can stop China from reunification,"
said the Chinese envoy.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Taiwan authorities to enter into political
talks with the Central Government under the principle of one
China. "This is in keeping with the fundamental interests of the
whole Chinese people, including the Taiwan compatriots," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qin made the statement following the General Committee of the
53rd Session of the General Assembly rejected the so-called
question of "Taiwan's representation at the United Nations". The
General Committee met on Friday to adopt agenda and allocate
items for the current session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth consecutive refusal since 1993 by the
General Committee to put the so-called question in the agenda
for the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"The outcome of today's meeting shows that there is only
China in the world, the Government of the People's Republic of
China is the only lawful government representing the Chinese
people as a whole and Taiwan is an inalienable part of China,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A majority of U.N. member states have reached a consensus that
the question of the Chinese representation at the United Nations
has already been a settled matter, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, the General Assembly at its 26th session adopted by
an overwhelming majority the historical significant resolution
2758 (XXVI). In the resolution, the Assembly clearly and
unequivocally recognized "that the representatives of the
government of the People's Republic of China are the only lawful
representatives of China to the United Nations and the People's
Republic of China is one of the five permanent representatives
of the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt which amounts to the denial of the resolution 2758
(XXVI) is doomed to failure, and so is any attempt to support
separatist illusions, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the General Committee's rejection, representatives
from many other countries took the floor to back Beijing's
stance on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
They said that the proposed "Taiwan's representation at the
United Nations" has long been a settled matter, and it simply
wastes time and energy to discuss this matter, which they said
is nothing but China's internal affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
