<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Helped by Wall Street Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Light gains on Wall Street
left European equity markets not far from previous closes on
Friday after registering heavy falls in morning trade on growing
concerns that U.S. President Clinton could face impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
London blue chip shares climbed off the floor to show only
modest losses at the close, pulled up by Wall Street's opening
gains.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 finished the day 18 lower at 5118, on moderate
volume of 868m shares traded.
</P>
<P>
The index recovered significantly from the early test below
5000, which followed yesterday's losses in the U.S. and some big
falls in Far East markets overnight.
</P>
<P>
Once again, U.S. stocks were the prime focus for London
traders, who watched President Clinton's emotional apology at a
White House prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
His performance helped the Dow shake off a soft start, but
traders didn't believe the markets' volatility was now over,
according to market analysts.
</P>
<P>
News that Russia's Duma endorsed Yevgeny Primakov as Prime
Minister, meanwhile, offered a much needed stabilizing influence.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares recovered from early lows, too,
lifted in part by Wall Street's attempts to hold gains, but
remained subdued.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra DAX closed 10.18 points lower at 4754.65. The index
earlier fell through key support levels of 4640 and 4650, reaching
a low of 4600.17.
</P>
<P>
A Frankfurt-based trader said that while there were no
fundamental reasons for the market's drop, "there are technical
influences at work, coming from the U.S., Russia and Asia."
</P>
<P>
After pulling the market lower late on Thursday, the weaker
dollar continued to unsettle German stocks.
</P>
<P>
A Financial Times report that Russia had delayed partial
payment of interest on debt to the Germany government for the
first time since its financial crisis erupted also unsettled
traders.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, shares recouped considerable ground from early lows,
benefiting from Wall Street's attempts to claw back Thursday's 250
point deficit. The Cac-40 index finished 11.01 lower points at
3578.34.  
</P>
</TEXT>
