<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Primakov Confirmation Marks Lull in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The State Duma's overwhelming
endorsement Friday of Yevgeny Primakov as prime minister marked a
much-needed lull in Russia's political storms, but ordinary
Russians are much eager to see whether the career diplomat can
bring goods back to store shelves and get prices down.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's nomination passed the lower house of parliament by a
vote of 317-63, far exceeding the required majority of 226 votes
in the 450-seat Duma, ending a 20-day government crisis.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of political standoff between President Boris
Yeltsin and the opposition erupted on August 23, when Yeltsin
abruptly fired the five-month-old cabinet of Sergei Kiriyenko and
named former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as premier the
next day.
</P>
<P>
After Chernomyrdin was voted down twice by the lower house,
Yeltsin succumbed to pressure from the major opposition parties
and named Acting Foreign Minister Primakov, an independent, as
premier.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's easy confirmation in the State Duma was widely
expected. Only the ultranationalist Liberal Democratic Party
decried the choice, branding him as "pro- American."
</P>
<P>
First, the choice of Primakov, a major concession on the part
of Yeltsin, basically met the minimum requirements by the
Communists, the largest faction in the Duma. Indeed, Yeltsin made
unprecedented concessions in the political standoff: he initialed
a political agreement which favors the Duma in front of leaders of
the opposition left; he agreed to the formation of a coalition
government; he agreed to amend the government law and allow his
authority to weaken in appointing cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also satisfied the opposition's demand to name
Communist deputy Yuri Maslyukov as first deputy prime minister and
ex-head of the Soviet State Bank Viktor Gerashchenko as governor
of the Central Bank of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Communists, the People's Power and the Agrarians control
211 seats in the Duma. If the 43 votes of the Yabloko, which was
the first to nominate Primakov as premier, the total of 254 votes
already exceed the required 226.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, as an independent, Primakov has been known to be not
interested in serving as head of the government. Neither did he
harbor any ambition for the 2000 presidential race, making him
apparently harmless to any party or politician.
</P>
<P>
And thirdly, against the backdrop riddle with political,
economic and social crises, most deputies appeared to be willing
to see an end to the government crisis, either out of
consideration of Russia's well-being, or for their own political
life.
</P>
<P>
Primakov has been pushed to the seat of premier under
extraordinary circumstances in an extraordinary period. The new
cabinet will face daunting challenges in harnessing the complex
political and economic situation, bringing the financial markets
back from the brink of collapse, and restoring people's
confidence.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the end of the latest government crisis
is only a lull in Russia's volatile political scene and in no way
marks a full stop to the political struggle between Yeltsin and
the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The lower house, especially the Communist-led opposition left,
will continue to press for constitutional revisions that require
Yeltsin to cede more of his powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0223 </DOCNO>
