<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Forecasts Large Crop Output This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Major crops prices are
likely to fall further because of forecasts for large corn,
soybean and wheat crops amid flat exports, the Agriculture
Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The department predicts that this year's record soybean harvest
of 2.91 billion bushels (one bushel of soybean is equivalent to
27.216 kg) will drop prices as low as 4.65 dollars a bushel,
compared with 6.45 dollars last year. The new figure represents
a 35-cent decrease from the August estimate and would be the
lowest soybean price since 1987.
</P>
<P>
Corn production is forecast at 9.74 billion bushels, which
would be the second-largest crop on record following 10.1 billion
bushels in 1994 and is 2 percent above the August prediction.
</P>
<P>
Although corn exports have improved slightly, prices are
forecast down 15 cents a bushel (one bushel of corn is about 25.42
kg) from last month to as low as 1.80 dollars a bushel as compared
with 2.45 dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
As for wheat, record per-acre yields of 43.3 bushels an acre
raised the overall forecast to 2.56 billion bushels, up 2 percent
from last year even though farmers planted less acreage this year.
</P>
<P>
But like the other crops, this bounty combined with stagnant
exports means prices as low as 2.50 dollars a bushel, down almost
a dollar from last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Proposed Taiwan's UN Reentry Ends with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The General Committee
of the 53rd Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations
on Friday decided not to put the so-called question of "Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations" in the agenda for the
current session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth consecutive refusal since 1993 by the General
Committee to include the alleged question, raised by a small
number of countries, in the agenda for the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Once again and with no exceptions, the so-called question of
"Tainwan's Representation at the United Nations" on Friday met
with strong opposition from a majority of justice-holding Member
States at the General Committee of the 53rd Session of the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
These countries voiced their opposition to the interference of
China's internal affairs by a small group of countries which
raised the so-called question of "Taiwan's representation at the
United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Representatives from some 40 countries, including Argentina,
Bangladesh, Chile, Egypt, Georgia, Germany, Iraq, Italy,
Kazakhstan, Kuwait, Libya, Mexico, Mongolia, Myammar, Nepal,
Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Saint Lucia and Tanzania, all took the floor
to back Beijing's position on Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
They said that there is only one China in the world, the
Government of the People's Republic of China is the sole
legitimate government of China as a whole, and Taiwan is only a
part of China.
</P>
<P>
Ahamad Kamal, Pakistani permanent representative to the
United Nations, voiced his hope that "it is the last time for
the General Committee to discuss this already settled matter."
</P>
<P>
"Every year we have wasted a lot of time and resources on
this kind of issue, and we hope to have more time to discuss
substantial issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi and Kuwaiti envoys told the General Committee of the 53rd
Session of the General Assembly that the so-called "Taiwan's
representation at the United Nations" has long been "a settled
matter" and "it simply wastes time" for Taiwan to seek reentry
into the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, the General Assembly at its 26th session adopted by an
overwhelming majority the historically significant resolution 2758
(XXVI). In this resolution, the Assembly clearly and unequivocally
recognized "that the representatives of the government of the
People's Republic of China are the only lawful representatives of
China to the United Nations and that the People's Republic of
China is one of the five permanent members of the Security
Council."
</P>
<P>
Also under the resolution, the Assembly decided to restore all
rights of the People's Republic of China in the United Nations and
to expel immediately the representative of Taiwan "from the place
which they unlawfully occupy at the United Nations and in all
organizations related to it."
</P>
<P>
The representative of Belarus, who described his country as "a
permanent supporter" of China's position on Taiwan issue, said
that Taiwan, as a province of China, lacks qualification for the
membership of the United Nations, which is an intergovernmental
organization composed of sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee met on Friday at the Conference Room 2 at
the U.N. headquarters to adopt the agenda and allocate items for
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Outside the conference hall, where the meeting is still under
way, diplomats from various countries showed cold shoulder to the
proposed Taiwan's UN reentry, saying that such a proposal "is
unpopular and doomed to failure."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980912.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duisenberg Warns Against Panic due to Crises in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- European Central Bank President
Wim Duisenberg Friday warned European investors against
overreactions to the financial crises in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Although the crisis in Russia and the continuing economic
meltdown in Asia are set to have a dampening effect on the world
economy, the situation should not be dramatized because of the
relative smaller economic scales of the crisis countries and their
limited shares in the world trade, Duisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for a panic," said Duisenberg after a
meeting of the governing council of the European Central Bank
(ECB) in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ECB chief said that he saw no immediate threat
for European economies from the U.S. dollar's sharp declines over
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
But he also warned that if the dollar continued to tumble
against European currencies, the competitiveness of European
economies could be undermined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
