<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Rises in Volatile Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rose
sharply in volatile trading Friday, with the Dow industrials up
almost 180 points.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street found encouragement in corporate profitability
pronouncements that overcame fears surrounding global economic
strife and unease over the fate of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average leaped 179.96 points, or by
2.4 percent, to close at 7,795.50. It gained 155.25 for the week.
But the Dow still was 16.5 percent below the July 17 record of
9,337.97 and 1.4 percent below where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, down 248.48 points Thursday, was off an additional
96.30 in the early trading, then shot up to a gain of 117.40,
before giving up some of that ground. By late afternoon it was
charging higher again, rising as much as 201.33 in the final hour
before fading somewhat heading into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Trading was heavy, with 817.7 million shares changing hands on
the New York Stock Exchange, but below Thursday's 875.7 million.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 28.87 to 1,009.06, and the
Nasdaq composite index rose 28.87 to 1,009.06.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 12.23 to 500.00, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.98 to 613.21.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 8.65 to 353.61.
</P>
<P>
The Asian markets, which closed earlier than Wall Street,
suffered great losses Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average plummeted 749.05 points,
or 5.12 percent, to close at 13,916.98. It was the largest one-day
point fall this year. The finish was just barely above the
Nikkei's 12-year closing low of 13,915.63 set on August 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
